gether in the woods. We got to know each other over appetizers by the fireplace (where most of us posted up every time we were inside!).</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>I felt so cozy sitting by the warm fire in the lodge as I got to know everyone. The comfortable atmosphere made it hard to be motivated to get up, but it was time to unpack and get settled in.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:image {\"id\":6691,\"linkDestination\":\"custom\"} -->\n<figure class=\"wp-block-image\"><a href=\"https://postcardstoseattle.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/02/cariboo-mountains-fireplace.jpg\"><img src=\"https://postcardstoseattle.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/02/cariboo-mountains-fireplace.jpg\" alt=\"cariboo mountains fireplace\" class=\"wp-image-6691\"/></a></figure>\n<!-- /wp:image -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>I loved that Silvertip Lodge had a bar complete with saloon doors. They had a huge selection of beer, wine, and hard alcohol to choose from, which was surprising for how remote we were.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>The staff was incredibly friendly and integrated themselves with us throughout the trip. Our outdoor guide and even the helicopter pilot were with us for meals, so I loved getting to know them.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>I was also grateful for how much they catered to food allergies/meal requests. I feel like a pain sometimes requesting meals without dairy or eggs and get embarrassed to ask, but they subtly put my custom meals in front of me each meal without making a big deal about it. Every meal was incredible, which again I didn’t expect being so far in the mountains.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:image {\"id\":6690,\"linkDestination\":\"custom\"} -->\n<figure class=\"wp-block-image\"><a href=\"https://postcardstoseattle.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/02/cariboo-mountains-lunch.jpg\"><img src=\"https://postcardstoseattle.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/02/cariboo-mountains-lunch.jpg\" alt=\"cariboo mountains lunch\" class=\"wp-image-6690\"/></a></figure>\n<!-- /wp:image -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading -->\n<h2>SILVERTIP LODGE ACCOMMODATIONS</h2>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>While everyone else claimed a room in the lodge, I stayed in a cabin outside. The cabin was adorable and I slept well with how quiet it was. I was surprised that it was warm inside and even had running water. The deck was perfect for viewing the stars at night, too. I had a feeling it would be hard to leave my cabin in the Cariboo Mountains by the end of the trip.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:image {\"id\":6673,\"linkDestination\":\"custom\"} -->\n<figure class=\"wp-block-image\"><a href=\"https://postcardstoseattle.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/02/cariboo-mountains-icicles.jpg\"><img src=\"https://postcardstoseattle.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/02/cariboo-mountains-icicles.jpg\" alt=\"cariboo mountains icicles\" class=\"wp-image-6673\"/></a></figure>\n<!-- /wp:image -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><em><strong>Read more:&nbsp;</strong></em><strong><a href=\"https://postcardstoseattle.com/outdoor-activities-you-need-to-do-on-vancouver-island/\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noreferrer noopener\">Outdoor Activities You Need to Do on Vancouver Island</a></strong></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:html -->\n<figure><iframe width=\"850\" height=\"200\" allowfullscreen=\"true\"></iframe></figure>\n<!-- /wp:html -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading -->\n<h2>SILVERTIP LODGE ACTIVITIES</h2>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>There are plenty of activities to do at Silvertip Lodge, whether you want to heli-ski or snowshoe.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":3} -->\n<h3>HELI-SKIING</h3>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Silvertip Lodge is most famous for their&nbsp;<a href=\"https://www.tripadvisor.com/Hotel_Review-g182161-d9860595-Reviews-Silvertip_Lodge_Heli_Skiing_Ltd-Quesnel_Cariboo_British_Columbia.html\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noreferrer noopener\">heli-skiing</a>. While we didn’t have a chance to do it during the trip, we flew by many of the mountains and saw the runs people normally go down. Something that’s unique about them is you can go on as many or as few runs as you want, and you don’t get charged by the meter like other places in Canada.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Booking a week heli-skiing in the Cariboo Mountains is the ultimate ski vacation. You can grab a group of friends and be the only one at Silvertip Lodge for the week. You get to essentially design your trip and where you want to go.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":3} -->\n<h3>SNOWSHOEING</h3>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>We did have plenty of time to explore the wilderness, however. The first morning we took the helicopter to go snowshoeing on the trails. I’ve done the activity before, but never with so much snow on the ground.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:image {\"id\":6683,\"linkDestination\":\"custom\"} -->\n<figure class=\"wp-block-image\"><a href=\"https://postcardstoseattle.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/02/cariboo-mountains-hiking.jpg\"><img src=\"https://postcardstoseattle.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/02/cariboo-mountains-hiking.jpg\" alt=\"cariboo mountains hiking\" class=\"wp-image-6683\"/></a></figure>\n<!-- /wp:image -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>We walked along a&nbsp;river and made it to a beautiful frozen waterfall. It made me think how I’d love to see a timelapse someday of when a waterfall starts to freeze. I loved how quiet it was in the woods and how it felt like we had it to ourselves.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:image {\"id\":6671,\"linkDestination\":\"custom\"} -->\n<figure class=\"wp-block-image\"><a href=\"https://postcardstoseattle.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/02/cariboo-mountains-waterfall.jpg\"><img src=\"https://postcardstoseattle.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/02/cariboo-mountains-waterfall.jpg\" alt=\"cariboo mountains waterfall\" class=\"wp-image-6671\"/></a></figure>\n<!-- /wp:image -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":3} -->\n<h3>CROSS-COUNTRY SKI</h3>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>You can also&nbsp;cross-country ski while staying at Silvertip Lodge. There are plenty of trails to go on that are well-marked, and an easy loop to follow is around the lake. It’s syrprinsingly a hard workout and a great way to see the area.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:image {\"id\":6685,\"linkDestination\":\"custom\"} -->\n<figure class=\"wp-block-image\"><a href=\"https://postcardstoseattle.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/02/cariboo-mountains-skis.jpg\"><img src=\"https://postcardstoseattle.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/02/cariboo-mountains-skis.jpg\" alt=\"cariboo mountains skis\" class=\"wp-image-6685\"/></a></figure>\n<!-- /wp:image -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>One trail I recommend going on is through the old growth forest towards the lake. These trees have been around for hundreds of years and are massive. It was peaceful to snowshoe through the trails here.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:html -->\n<figure><iframe width=\"850\" height=\"200\" allowfullscreen=\"true\"></iframe></figure>\n<!-- /wp:html -->\n\n<!-- wp:image {\"id\":6672,\"linkDestination\":\"custom\"} -->\n<figure class=\"wp-block-image\"><a href=\"https://postcardstoseattle.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/02/cariboo-mountains-growth-forest.jpg\"><img src=\"https://postcardstoseattle.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/02/cariboo-mountains-growth-forest.jpg\" alt=\"cariboo mountains growth forest\" class=\"wp-image-6672\"/></a></figure>\n<!-- /wp:image -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>While I love winter sports, bringing your own equipment takes up so much space. I loved that I didn’t need to bring any equipment with me to enjoy the different activities. They&nbsp;have a ski shop where you can borrow what you need and even head out on your own for a morning snowshoe if you prefer.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Inside the lodge, they also had plenty of clothes and accessories for sale in case you forgot something. This was extremely convenient, as it’s not like you can just walk to the store in the Cariboo Mountains.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:image {\"id\":6682,\"linkDestination\":\"custom\"} -->\n<figure class=\"wp-block-image\"><a href=\"https://postcardstoseattle.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/02/cariboo-mountains-ski-shop.jpg\"><img src=\"https://postcardstoseattle.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/02/cariboo-mountains-ski-shop.jpg\" alt=\"cariboo mountains ski shop\" class=\"wp-image-6682\"/></a></figure>\n<!-- /wp:image -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Winter is a popular time to visit, there’s plenty to do during the summer too. They’re known for their fishing and they own 14 acres, so you’re sure to catch some fish.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:image {\"id\":6679,\"linkDestination\":\"custom\"} -->\n<figure class=\"wp-block-image\"><a href=\"https://postcardstoseattle.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/02/cariboo-mountains-sunset.jpg\"><img src=\"https://postcardstoseattle.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/02/cariboo-mountains-sunset.jpg\" alt=\"cariboo mountains sunset\" class=\"wp-image-6679\"/></a></figure>\n<!-- /wp:image -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Of course, what would a cold day exploring outside be without ending the day in a hot tub overlooking the lake? They have a small building with a steam room, hot tub, and even a massage room. This was the perfect way to unwind after a long day in the cold.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:image {\"id\":6681,\"linkDestination\":\"custom\"} -->\n<figure class=\"wp-block-image\"><a href=\"https://postcardstoseattle.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/02/cariboo-mountains-hot-tub.jpg\"><img src=\"https://postcardstoseattle.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/02/cariboo-mountains-hot-tub.jpg\" alt=\"cariboo mountains hot tub\" class=\"wp-image-6681\"/></a></figure>\n<!-- /wp:image -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Our days there involved playing outside, eating delicious food, celebrating the day over drinks, sleeping well, and then repeating. My only regret was that I wasn’t there longer. When you have to get on the final helicopter ride to leave Silvertip Lodge, you might shed a tear too.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:image {\"id\":6675,\"linkDestination\":\"custom\"} -->\n<figure class=\"wp-block-image\"><a href=\"https://postcardstoseattle.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/02/cariboo-mountains-silvertip-lodge.jpg\"><img src=\"https://postcardstoseattle.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/02/cariboo-mountains-silvertip-lodge.jpg\" alt=\"cariboo mountains silvertip lodge\" class=\"wp-image-6675\"/></a></figure>\n<!-- /wp:image -->\n\n<!-- wp:separator -->\n<hr class=\"wp-block-separator\"/>\n<!-- /wp:separator -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><em>This post was in partnership with the Cariboo Chilcotin Coast Tourism Association, but all opinions are my own.</em></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->', 'EXPLORING THE WILDERNESS IN THE CARIBOO MOUNTAINS', '', 'inherit', 'closed', 'closed', '', '219-revision-v1', '', '', '2019-04-20 04:41:17', '2019-04-20 04:41:17', '', 219, 'http://localhost/wordpress/2019/04/20/219-revision-v1/', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(225, 1, '2019-04-20 06:02:37', '2019-04-20 06:02:37', '<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>One of the reasons I started my blog was to research what all there is to do in the Pacific Northwest. I’ve lived in Seattle for over 20 years, but there are still many places I’ve never been to. However, one of the struggles I have when traveling is figuring out what to do with my two dogs. My goal is to always find dog-friendly vacations in the Pacific Northwest so they can come with me.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>My rescue dogs, a Border Collie mix and a German Shepherd mix, aren’t exactly small, so it’s not easy to take them everywhere I go. I’ve been pleasantly surprised to find that many places in the Pacific Northwest are dog-friendly.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading -->\n<h2>DOG-FRIENDLY VACATIONS IN WASHINGTON</h2>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>There are&nbsp;so many dog-friendly vacations in Washington that it’d be impossible to list them all. Here are just a few of the places I recommend going to if you want to go on a pet-friendly vacation in the state.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":3} -->\n<h3>BLAINE</h3>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>The city of Blaine is the last one you’ll go through in Washington right before you hit the Canadian border. You don’t have to go to Canada to have an adventure, however. Blaine is located right on the water and is perfect for taking&nbsp;<strong>long hikes</strong>&nbsp;with your pup or even kayaking if they like to do that.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>While there are plenty of places to stay, I highly recommend booking a room at&nbsp;<a href=\"https://www.booking.com/hotel/us/semiahmoo-resort-and-spa.html\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noreferrer noopener\"><strong>Semiahmoo Resort</strong></a>. I stayed here with my two pups and absolutely loved their stay. This dog-friendly hotel&nbsp;makes your pups feel extremely welcome during their stay. As soon as we got in the room, they ran to their food and water bowls which already had dog treats in them.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>They also had a few gifts left for them, including adorable Semiahoo bandanas, tennis bowls, and a pop-up water bowl. We had a room right on the water so it was easy to take them outside to the bathroom and to walk around the beach. It costs&nbsp;<strong>$25 per dog per night</strong>&nbsp;to bring them, which was more than worth it to be able to bring them on vacation and have them enjoy it too.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><a href=\"https://www.tripadvisor.com/Hotel_Review-g58359-d4563441-Reviews-Semiahmoo_Resort-Blaine_Washington.html\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noreferrer noopener\">BOOK YOUR ROOM HERE!</a></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:image {\"id\":8896,\"align\":\"center\"} -->\n<div class=\"wp-block-image\"><figure class=\"aligncenter\"><img src=\"https://postcardstoseattle.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/11/dog-friendly-vacations-semiahmoo.jpg\" alt=\"dog friendly vacations semiahmoo\" class=\"wp-image-8896\"/></figure></div>\n<!-- /wp:image -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":3} -->\n<h3>SEABROOK</h3>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Seabrook is a small beach community right along the Pacific Ocean in Washington. It’s about a&nbsp;<strong>3-hour drive from Seattle</strong>&nbsp;or Portland and has a ton of features that make it family-friendly…for both humans and dogs alike.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>There are no hotels in this community, but rather character-filled homes for rent. This is ideal because you can search for vacation rentals that allow pets. The homes that we’ve stayed in with our English bulldog, Nala, included toys, beds, water bowls, and more, which made it great for lightening the packing load! So make sure to check the rental listing for details about what they’ll have for your pet.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Remember those movies&nbsp;<em>Pleasantville</em>&nbsp;and&nbsp;<em>Now and Then</em>? This community is like that. Pedestrians with their beach cruiser bikes, rollerblades, and pets rule the streets. There’s plenty of sidewalks and&nbsp;<strong>grassy/park areas</strong>&nbsp;to enjoy with your dog. This setup makes it safe, particularly if your dog prefers being unleashed.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:image {\"id\":8895,\"align\":\"center\"} -->\n<div class=\"wp-block-image\"><figure class=\"aligncenter\"><img src=\"https://postcardstoseattle.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/11/dog-friendly-vacations-seabrook-1.jpg\" alt=\"dog friendly vacations seabrook\" class=\"wp-image-8895\"/></figure></div>\n<!-- /wp:image -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>My favorite thing about&nbsp;<a href=\"https://www.seabrookwa.com/\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noreferrer noopener\">Seabrook</a>&nbsp;is the trails. Most of them lead to the beach, which includes dunes and sand as for as the eye can see. It’s perfect for your beach-loving dog to run free. Or, if your dog is like mine and can’t be trusted running free, there’s plenty of space so it’s easy to avoid other dogs.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Dogs are considered part of the family in this town, so you’ll see them accompanying their owners doing various activities. If you’re traveling in the fall, you can bring your dog digging for razor-clams. There’s a dog-friendly&nbsp;<strong>farmers market</strong>&nbsp;on Saturdays.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>You can also drive the 1-2 hours to the&nbsp;<strong>Olympic National Park</strong>&nbsp;to explore the Hoh Rainforest and other popular beaches on the Olympic Peninsula. No matter what you prefer to do, Seabrook is the perfect place to experience it with your dog!</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><em>Adria Saracino,&nbsp;<a href=\"http://www.emeraldpalate.com/\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noreferrer noopener\">The Emerald Palate</a></em></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":3} -->\n<h3>PORT TOWNSEND</h3>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Port Townsend is a cute little Victorian port town on the Olympic Peninsula and a fun place to visit with your dog. There are many&nbsp;<strong>dog-friendly parks</strong>&nbsp;and trails in the area.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><strong>Chetzemoka Park</strong>&nbsp;offers beach access and a beautiful rose archway in the spring. Enjoy historic buildings, the beach, a lighthouse, miles of trails, and old military bunkers at&nbsp;<strong>Ft. Warden State Park</strong>&nbsp;(a&nbsp;<a href=\"https://www.discoverpass.wa.gov/\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noreferrer noopener\">Discover Pass</a>&nbsp;is required for parking here). On a clear day, you can walk the&nbsp;<strong>Larry Scott Waterfront Trail</strong>and enjoy spectacular views of Mount Baker and Mount Rainier – two of the largest mountains in Washington State.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:image {\"id\":8892,\"align\":\"center\"} -->\n<div class=\"wp-block-image\"><figure class=\"aligncenter\"><img src=\"https://postcardstoseattle.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/11/dog-friendly-vacations-port-townsend.jpg\" alt=\"port townsend pet friendly vacation\" class=\"wp-image-8892\"/></figure></div>\n<!-- /wp:image -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>After a romp in one of the many parks, or along the beach, you can wander the beautiful, historic downtown area and grab lunch with your pooch infamous&nbsp;<strong>Waterfront Pizza</strong>&nbsp;or cute&nbsp;<strong>Nifty Fifty’s Soda Fountain&nbsp;and Diner</strong>&nbsp;and eat outside on a nearby picnic table or bench. Your dog can even accompany you on one of&nbsp;Port Townsend’s famous&nbsp;sidewalk tours.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>There are several dog-friendly hotels in Port Townsend including the quirky&nbsp;<a href=\"https://www.booking.com/hotel/us/palace-port-townsend.html\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noreferrer noopener\"><strong>Palace Hotel</strong></a>, a restored brothel that operated from 1925 to 1933,&nbsp;<a href=\"https://www.tripadvisor.com/Hotel_Review-g58687-d115747-Reviews-Tides_Inn-Port_Townsend_Washington.html\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noreferrer noopener\"><strong>The Tides Inn and Suites</strong></a>, which sits on the waterfront and was featured in the movie&nbsp;<em>An Officer and a Gentleman</em>, and the&nbsp;<a href=\"https://www.hotelscombined.com/Hotel/Bishop_Victorian_Hotel.htm\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noreferrer noopener\"><strong>Bishop Victorian Hotel</strong></a>.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><em>Jessica Williams,&nbsp;<a href=\"http://youdidwhatwithyourweiner.com/\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noreferrer noopener\">You Did What With Your Wiener</a></em></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":3} -->\n<h3>HOOD CANAL</h3>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>One of the best dog-friendly vacations in the Pacific Northwest that’s not too far from Seattle is&nbsp;<a href=\"https://postcardstoseattle.com/relaxing-on-hood-canal/\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noreferrer noopener\">Hood Canal</a>. There are plenty of hikes to go on around the area that you’re allowed to bring your pup with. Just make sure you double check them before you start, as not each one permits dogs. Some of the ones that do include&nbsp;<strong>Ranger Hole Trail</strong>&nbsp;and&nbsp;<strong>Lena Lake</strong>. Your dog is also welcome to eat with you at the restaurant&nbsp;<strong>Cafe Nola.</strong></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>When looking for accommodation,&nbsp;<a href=\"https://www.tripadvisor.com/Hotel_Review-g58796-d100695-Reviews-Alderbrook_Resort_Spa-Union_Washington.html\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noreferrer noopener\"><strong>Alderbrook Resort and Spa</strong></a>&nbsp;is right on the water and has many activities for your dog to do. When you book a pet-friendly room, they’ll put you in a room that has dog beds and food and water bowls for them. I loved not having to bring my own, as I’m usually a light traveler. I was also in a room on ground level with a door that led right to the grass, so it was really easy when I had to take my dogs out.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>In addition, you’re able to bring your&nbsp;dog to enjoy happy hour outdoors with you (as long as they’re on their leash and well-behaved, of course). There are three miles of&nbsp;<strong>hiking trails</strong>&nbsp;that are found behind the resort so both you and your dog can get exercise in during your stay.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><a href=\"https://www.hotelscombined.com/Hotel/Alderbrook_Resort_Union_Washington.htm\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noreferrer noopener\">BOOK YOUR ROOM HERE!</a></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:image {\"id\":8884,\"align\":\"center\"} -->\n<div class=\"wp-block-image\"><figure class=\"aligncenter\"><img src=\"https://postcardstoseattle.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/11/dog-friendly-vacations-hood-canal.jpg\" alt=\"alderbrook hood canal dog friendly\" class=\"wp-image-8884\"/></figure></div>\n<!-- /wp:image -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":3} -->\n<h3>FORT FLAGLER</h3>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Fort Flagler is the perfect&nbsp;<strong>Washington state park</strong>&nbsp;to take your family to and to also take your family dog to as well!&nbsp; For either a day trip or a camping trip this state park is perfect for dogs and kids of any age.&nbsp; We had forgotten dog&nbsp;treats for our dog and the little store at the park had treats for him and even sold food in case you hadn’t brought enough for your pet.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Fort Flagler State Park has&nbsp;<strong>5 miles of maintained trails</strong>&nbsp;throughout the park and also&nbsp;<strong>2 miles of beach trails</strong>&nbsp;wore the dog out so he slept soundly in the tent.&nbsp; The campground hosts made sure everyone was following the leash and tethering rules so we never had an issue of someone else’s&nbsp;dog walking into our campsite.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:image {\"id\":8906,\"align\":\"center\"} -->\n<div class=\"wp-block-image\"><figure class=\"aligncenter\"><img src=\"https://postcardstoseattle.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/11/dog-friendly-vacations-fort-flagler-2.jpg\" alt=\"fort flagler pet friendly vacations\" class=\"wp-image-8906\"/></figure></div>\n<!-- /wp:image -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading -->\n<h2>DOG-FRIENDLY VACATIONS IN OREGON</h2>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Similar to Oregon, there are many places in Oregon to go on a dog-friendly vacation as well!</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":3} -->\n<h3>ASHLAND</h3>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>You and your pup will be right at home walking around charming Ashland, Oregon. Surrounded by mountains and just three hours from the Oregon Coast, this southern Oregon town is a great spot for a dog-friendly weekend getaway. Though the park in the center of town doesn’t allow dogs, the main streets in town have large sidewalks, and you’ll find plenty of restaurants and coffee shops with outdoor seating for you and your dog.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Be sure to stop in at&nbsp;<strong>Bloomsbury Coffee</strong>, where dogs are welcome on the outdoor tables or back porch. If you need to get in a longer outing, Noble Coffee Roasters is a 10-minute walk from downtown and also has outdoor seating perfect for you and your dog.&nbsp;<strong>Wellness Pet Supplies</strong>, a local natural pet store, is around the corner from Noble Coffee Roasters – stop in for a visit and a dog treat. Smithfield’s Restaurant and Bar, specializing in local, sustainable dining, is in the heart of town and offers dog-friendly seating on the porch.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:image {\"id\":8887,\"align\":\"center\"} -->\n<div class=\"wp-block-image\"><figure class=\"aligncenter\"><img src=\"https://postcardstoseattle.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/11/dog-friendly-vacations-ashland.jpg\" alt=\"ashland dog friendly weekend getaway\" class=\"wp-image-8887\"/></figure></div>\n<!-- /wp:image -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Ashland is best known for the&nbsp;<strong>Oregon Shakespeare Festival</strong>. While the theater isn’t pet-friendly, if you decide to see a play (which you should!), consider a matinee, and visit&nbsp;<a href=\"https://rover.com/\">Rover.com</a>&nbsp;for a list of pet sitters in the area that offer doggie daycare.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Where to stay: In addition to dog-friendly options you may find on Airbnb (my go-to when traveling with my dog), the historic&nbsp;<a href=\"https://www.tripadvisor.com/Hotel_Review-g29998-d225890-Reviews-Ashland_Springs_Hotel-Ashland_Oregon.html\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noreferrer noopener\">Ashland Springs Hotel</a>&nbsp;is the perfect place to stay, and they allow pet</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":3} -->\n<h3>PORTLAND</h3>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Nestled in the heart of downtown Portland, you’ll find the perfect respite for a pet-friendly vacation at the&nbsp;<a href=\"https://www.tripadvisor.com/Hotel_Review-g52024-d12124883-Reviews-AC_Hotel_Portland_Downtown-Portland_Oregon.html\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noreferrer noopener\"><strong>AC Hotel</strong></a>.&nbsp; The minimalist European design and smart in-room features, provide an experience unparalleled&nbsp;with your typical family (&amp; pet) friendly hotel.&nbsp; The style, comfort and general aesthetic are what you’d expect from a Marriott property, but with the flavors of PDX.&nbsp;<strong>AC Hotel pet policy</strong>:&nbsp;&nbsp;<em>Dogs only, 2 max per room, $100 non-refundable deposit.</em></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>You’re close to a variety of leash-friendly activities like the&nbsp;<strong>Portland Saturday Market, Tom McCall Waterfront Park</strong>, and pet-friendly restaurant patios and coffee shops like&nbsp;<strong>Java Hound Coffee Bar</strong>&nbsp;and&nbsp;<strong>Lucky Labrador Beer Hall</strong>. When you’re ready to venture out of the city for a bit, head to&nbsp;<strong>Walton Beach</strong>on Sauvie Island, proclaimed to be one of the best sandy beaches in Portland, alongside the Columbia River.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:image {\"id\":8893,\"align\":\"center\"} -->\n<div class=\"wp-block-image\"><figure class=\"aligncenter\"><img src=\"https://postcardstoseattle.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/11/dog-friendly-vacations-portland.jpg\" alt=\"portland dog friendly hotel\" class=\"wp-image-8893\"/></figure></div>\n<!-- /wp:image -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Note:&nbsp;<strong>Collins Beach</strong>, which is just down the road is a clothing-optional beach so&nbsp;keep that in mind regardless of your preference. &nbsp;There’s visible signage at each beach – so no worries!</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Whether you’re in the mood for a simple staycation, market meandering or foodie crawl, it’s easy to enjoy Portland with your best friend in tow.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":3} -->\n<h3>CENTRAL OREGON/BEND</h3>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Head to&nbsp;Central&nbsp;Oregon&nbsp;and you’ll find a region worth visiting year-round with your dog. Bend was named<strong>DogTown USA in 2012</strong>, thanks to its many dog-friendly businesses and dining establishments.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Central&nbsp;Oregon&nbsp;is best enjoyed outdoors, with summer sports including&nbsp;<strong>paddling, hiking, cycling, white water rafting, and golfing.</strong>&nbsp;Dogs are often seen on the river with their owners, as well as on many of the trails. In fact, there are dozens of off-leash city parks and National Forests in the area.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>In winter, areas of the High Desert turn into a snowy wonderland.&nbsp;Wanoga, Edison and Kapka Sno-Parks have dog-friendly&nbsp;<strong>cross-country ski and snowshoe trails</strong>.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:image {\"id\":8907,\"align\":\"center\"} -->\n<div class=\"wp-block-image\"><figure class=\"aligncenter\"><img src=\"https://postcardstoseattle.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/11/dog-friendly-vacations-oregon.jpg\" alt=\"bend oregon dog friendly weekend getaway\" class=\"wp-image-8907\"/></figure></div>\n<!-- /wp:image -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Oregonians on vacation often stay in Bend or nearby resorts like&nbsp;<a href=\"https://www.tripadvisor.com/Hotel_Review-g51788-d1854270-Reviews-Black_Butte_Resort-Camp_Sherman_Central_Oregon_Oregon.html\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noreferrer noopener\"><strong>Black Butte</strong></a>&nbsp;and&nbsp;<a href=\"https://www.hotelscombined.com/Hotel/Sunriver_Resort.htm\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noreferrer noopener\"><strong>Sunriver</strong></a>. Dog-friendly accommodations include&nbsp;<a href=\"https://www.hotelscombined.com/Hotel/McMenamins_Old_St_Francis_School.htm\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noreferrer noopener\"><strong>McMenamins</strong></a>&nbsp;and&nbsp;<strong>Lucky Vacation Rental</strong>. But to truly get off-the-beaten-path, check out&nbsp;Redmond&nbsp;Oregon&nbsp;and its surroundings for the same great activities with even fewer crowds.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":3} -->\n<h3>MT. HOOD</h3>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>One of my favorite&nbsp;weekend getaways in the Pacific Northwest is the Mt. Hood area due to how many outdoor activities there are. Whether you go in the summer or the winter, it makes for a great dog-friendly vacation. There are tons of trails to hike on during the summer that both you and your dog will love.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>In the winter, there are tons of activities that you can bring your dogs on. Check out one of the many&nbsp;<strong>cross-country skiing trails or go snowshoeing</strong>&nbsp;for a fun-filled day. Just make sure to keep your dog warm enough so they don’t freeze from being in cold weather for too long. Afterward, head to one of the dog-friendly breweries like&nbsp;<strong>Mt. Hood Brewing Co.</strong>&nbsp;to enjoy a pint.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>For a&nbsp;dog-friendly hotel in Oregon that everyone will enjoy, check out&nbsp;<a href=\"https://www.tripadvisor.com/Hotel_Review-g52127-d114274-Reviews-Resort_at_The_Mountain_BW_Premier_Collection-Welches_Clackamas_County_Oregon.html\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noreferrer noopener\"><strong>Mt. Hood Oregon Resort</strong></a>. It’s a great base for doing pet-friendly activities during the day in Mt. Hood Territory. They had a huge room that my dogs loved running around and trails on the property that I could walk them on in the morning. For humans, they have a restaurant, bar, fitness center, and even a spa for when you want to relax.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:image {\"id\":8890,\"align\":\"center\"} -->\n<div class=\"wp-block-image\"><figure class=\"aligncenter\"><img src=\"https://postcardstoseattle.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/11/dog-friendly-vacations-mt-hood.jpg\" alt=\"dog friendly vacations mt hood\" class=\"wp-image-8890\"/></figure></div>\n<!-- /wp:image -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading -->\n<h2>DOG-FRIENDLY VACATIONS IN BRITISH COLUMBIA</h2>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>If you want an adventurous dog-friendly vacation, head to Canada. There are so many beautiful forests, beaches, and more to explore.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":3} -->\n<h3>HOW TO BRING YOUR DOG TO CANADA</h3>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>When you’re planning your trip to Canada, it’s important to recognize that you can’t just bring your dog over the border without the&nbsp;<strong>proper documentation</strong>. If you just show up, they’ll quickly deny you entry and you’ll be headed back home. Before you go on your dog-friendly vacation, make sure your dog has everything that’s required. The best way is to check out the official&nbsp;<a href=\"http://www.inspection.gc.ca/animals/terrestrial-animals/imports/policies/live-animals/pets/dogs/eng/1331876172009/1331876307796\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noreferrer noopener\">Canadian inspection website</a>, which lets you put in exactly where you’re coming from and specific information about your dog.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Taking your dog to Canada isn’t that hard, as most times you’ll just need a&nbsp;<strong>rabies certification.</strong>&nbsp;This needs to be in English or French, state what the dog’s color, breed, and weight is, list what type of rabies vaccine was used, what the serial number is, and how long it’s valid for. You can usually just get this from your vet (mine was able to email me).</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":3} -->\n<h3>VANCOUVER ISLAND</h3>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Vancouver Island is one of the best dog-friendly vacations to take in Canada, as it’s so expansive. At over 290 miles long and 62 miles wide, you can easily spend a week or longer exploring. Your dogs will love&nbsp;<strong>running along the beaches</strong>&nbsp;and playing in the water. There are also hundreds of different&nbsp;<strong>hikes to go on</strong>and other fun&nbsp;<a href=\"https://postcardstoseattle.com/outdoor-activities-you-need-to-do-on-vancouver-island/\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noreferrer noopener\">outdoor activities</a>.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>There are many places to stay on the island during your pet-friendly vacation, including campsites or vacation rentals. If you’d prefer to be in a resort, check out&nbsp;<a href=\"https://www.booking.com/hotel/ca/tigh-na-mara-resort.html\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noreferrer noopener\"><strong>Tigh-Na-Mara Resort</strong></a>. I’ve stayed here multiple times now. I love that it’s secluded in the woods, yet has access to the beach. You can stay in one of their pet-friendly cabins while there. They’re perfect for a Pacific Northwest vacation at any time of the year.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:image {\"id\":8897,\"align\":\"center\"} -->\n<div class=\"wp-block-image\"><figure class=\"aligncenter\"><img src=\"https://postcardstoseattle.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/11/dog-friendly-vacations-vancouver-island.jpg\" alt=\"vancouver island pet friendly\" class=\"wp-image-8897\"/></figure></div>\n<!-- /wp:image -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":3} -->\n<h3>WHISTLER</h3>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Whistler is a great place to have a dog-friendly vacation in the Pacific Northwest. You’ll see dogs everywhere you go, whether it’s in the main village or around town. There are plenty of&nbsp;<strong>hiking trails</strong>around the area that you can access most times of the year.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>There are a ton of dog-friendly hotels in Whistler as well. I stayed at the&nbsp;<a href=\"https://www.tripadvisor.com/Hotel_Review-g154948-d293175-Reviews-Four_Seasons_Resort_and_Residences_Whistler-Whistler_British_Columbia.html\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noreferrer noopener\"><strong>Four Seasons Resort Whistler</strong></a>last time I was in town and was surprised to see a ton of dogs. Other pet-friendly hotels in Whistler include&nbsp;<strong>Pan Pacific Whistler, Fairmont Chateau Whistler, and Crystal Lodge.</strong>&nbsp;They all have different pet policies, so call ahead of time. You’ll want to confirm the price and any restrictions on the size and number of dogs.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:image {\"id\":8905,\"align\":\"center\"} -->\n<div class=\"wp-block-image\"><figure class=\"aligncenter\"><img src=\"https://postcardstoseattle.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/11/dog-friendly-vacations-whistler.jpg\" alt=\"whistler dog friendly\" class=\"wp-image-8905\"/></figure></div>\n<!-- /wp:image -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading -->\n<h2>TIPS FOR TRAVELING WITH YOUR DOGS</h2>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>I’ve been on dozens of different vacations with my pups at this point. Here are some quick tips to consider before going on your dog-friendly vacation in the Pacific Northwest.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:list -->\n<ul><li>Call the hotel ahead to confirm you can bring your dog and see what the pet fee is.</li><li>Make sure to have portable water bowls for them so they can stay hydrated during the day.</li><li>Bring their regular dog food so they don’t get sick on vacation trying something new (or human food).</li><li>Pack poop bags to pick up after them.</li><li>Always have them on a leash with their collar on and don’t assume an area is off-leash unless it’s stated.</li><li>Make time to walk them or take them to a dog park to get their energy out. No one likes being cooped up in a car, dogs included!</li></ul>\n<!-- /wp:list -->', 'BEST DOG-FRIENDLY VACATIONS IN THE PACIFIC NORTHWEST', '', 'inherit', 'closed', 'closed', '', '217-revision-v1', '', '', '2019-04-20 06:02:37', '2019-04-20 06:02:37', '', 217, 'http://localhost/wordpress/2019/04/20/217-revision-v1/', 0, 'revision', '', 0);
INSERT INTO `wp_posts` (`ID`, `post_author`, `post_date`, `post_date_gmt`, `post_content`, `post_title`, `post_excerpt`, `post_status`, `comment_status`, `ping_status`, `post_password`, `post_name`, `to_ping`, `pinged`, `post_modified`, `post_modified_gmt`, `post_content_filtered`, `post_parent`, `guid`, `menu_order`, `post_type`, `post_mime_type`, `comment_count`) VALUES
(226, 1, '2019-04-20 06:03:01', '2019-04-20 06:03:01', '<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>The Cariboo Mountains are located in the eastern part of British Columbia in Canada. I recently went there for the first time this winter and stayed at Silvertip Lodge on Quesnel Lake. It’s so remote that you have to take a helicopter there, as it’s not accessible by road. When I heard that, I knew it was my kind of place!</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>The Silvertip Lodge was built in the 1960s and was originally made for hunters and fishermen. While fishing is still popular here, skiers from all over the world come here to experience the area in the winter, when they can heli-ski. If you love being out in the middle of nowhere, you’ll absolutely love this lodge in the Cariboo Mountains.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading -->\n<h2>HOW TO GET TO SILVERTIP LODGE</h2>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>The helicopter picks you up from William Lake Airport, which you can get to from Vancouver International Airport on Pacific Coastal Airlines. It’s about an hour flight to get there. Once the helicopter picks you up, it’s about a 45-minute ride to&nbsp;<a href=\"http://silvertipheliskiing.com/\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noreferrer noopener\">Silvertip Lodge</a>.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:image {\"id\":6686,\"linkDestination\":\"custom\"} -->\n<figure class=\"wp-block-image\"><a href=\"https://postcardstoseattle.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/02/cariboo-mountains-astar-helicopter.jpg\"><img src=\"https://postcardstoseattle.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/02/cariboo-mountains-astar-helicopter.jpg\" alt=\"cariboo mountains astar helicopter\" class=\"wp-image-6686\"/></a></figure>\n<!-- /wp:image -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>This was my first time in a helicopter and I thought I might get motion sick, but I felt completely fine. I was surprised that the helicopter was so steady as we flew through the sky. The views of the mountains and frozen lakes were incredible to see from the air.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Getting out of the helicopter for the first time was a bit tricky, as you have to crouch down while moving to the side. The blades were running quickly so it could take off after dropping us off, but it blew snow everywhere. You even have to hold on to your beanie to make sure it doesn’t fly off your head when it leaves!</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:image {\"id\":6677,\"linkDestination\":\"custom\"} -->\n<figure class=\"wp-block-image\"><a href=\"https://postcardstoseattle.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/02/cariboo-mountains-helicopter-view.jpg\"><img src=\"https://postcardstoseattle.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/02/cariboo-mountains-helicopter-view.jpg\" alt=\"cariboo mountains helicopter view\" class=\"wp-image-6677\"/></a></figure>\n<!-- /wp:image -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading -->\n<h2>STAYING AT SILVERTIP LODGE</h2>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Once the helicopter left and we stepped into the lodge, it felt like home. The main building of Silvertip Lodge is a large A-frame building that has eight rooms, a living room, dining room, and bar. We were greeted with fresh cookies and hot coffee while getting a rundown of the next few days. Considering the temperature was below freezing outside in the Cariboo Mountains, this was the perfect way to get greeted.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Even though I had just met the group who was staying at the lodge with me, it quickly felt like we were close friends vacationing together in the woods. We got to know each other over appetizers by the fireplace (where most of us posted up every time we were inside!).</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>I felt so cozy sitting by the warm fire in the lodge as I got to know everyone. The comfortable atmosphere made it hard to be motivated to get up, but it was time to unpack and get settled in.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:image {\"id\":6691,\"linkDestination\":\"custom\"} -->\n<figure class=\"wp-block-image\"><a href=\"https://postcardstoseattle.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/02/cariboo-mountains-fireplace.jpg\"><img src=\"https://postcardstoseattle.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/02/cariboo-mountains-fireplace.jpg\" alt=\"cariboo mountains fireplace\" class=\"wp-image-6691\"/></a></figure>\n<!-- /wp:image -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>I loved that Silvertip Lodge had a bar complete with saloon doors. They had a huge selection of beer, wine, and hard alcohol to choose from, which was surprising for how remote we were.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>The staff was incredibly friendly and integrated themselves with us throughout the trip. Our outdoor guide and even the helicopter pilot were with us for meals, so I loved getting to know them.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>I was also grateful for how much they catered to food allergies/meal requests. I feel like a pain sometimes requesting meals without dairy or eggs and get embarrassed to ask, but they subtly put my custom meals in front of me each meal without making a big deal about it. Every meal was incredible, which again I didn’t expect being so far in the mountains.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:image {\"id\":6690,\"linkDestination\":\"custom\"} -->\n<figure class=\"wp-block-image\"><a href=\"https://postcardstoseattle.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/02/cariboo-mountains-lunch.jpg\"><img src=\"https://postcardstoseattle.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/02/cariboo-mountains-lunch.jpg\" alt=\"cariboo mountains lunch\" class=\"wp-image-6690\"/></a></figure>\n<!-- /wp:image -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading -->\n<h2>SILVERTIP LODGE ACCOMMODATIONS</h2>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>While everyone else claimed a room in the lodge, I stayed in a cabin outside. The cabin was adorable and I slept well with how quiet it was. I was surprised that it was warm inside and even had running water. The deck was perfect for viewing the stars at night, too. I had a feeling it would be hard to leave my cabin in the Cariboo Mountains by the end of the trip.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:image {\"id\":6673,\"linkDestination\":\"custom\"} -->\n<figure class=\"wp-block-image\"><a href=\"https://postcardstoseattle.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/02/cariboo-mountains-icicles.jpg\"><img src=\"https://postcardstoseattle.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/02/cariboo-mountains-icicles.jpg\" alt=\"cariboo mountains icicles\" class=\"wp-image-6673\"/></a></figure>\n<!-- /wp:image -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading -->\n<h2>SILVERTIP LODGE ACTIVITIES</h2>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>There are plenty of activities to do at Silvertip Lodge, whether you want to heli-ski or snowshoe.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":3} -->\n<h3>HELI-SKIING</h3>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Silvertip Lodge is most famous for their&nbsp;<a href=\"https://www.tripadvisor.com/Hotel_Review-g182161-d9860595-Reviews-Silvertip_Lodge_Heli_Skiing_Ltd-Quesnel_Cariboo_British_Columbia.html\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noreferrer noopener\">heli-skiing</a>. While we didn’t have a chance to do it during the trip, we flew by many of the mountains and saw the runs people normally go down. Something that’s unique about them is you can go on as many or as few runs as you want, and you don’t get charged by the meter like other places in Canada.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Booking a week heli-skiing in the Cariboo Mountains is the ultimate ski vacation. You can grab a group of friends and be the only one at Silvertip Lodge for the week. You get to essentially design your trip and where you want to go.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":3} -->\n<h3>SNOWSHOEING</h3>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>We did have plenty of time to explore the wilderness, however. The first morning we took the helicopter to go snowshoeing on the trails. I’ve done the activity before, but never with so much snow on the ground.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:image {\"id\":6683,\"linkDestination\":\"custom\"} -->\n<figure class=\"wp-block-image\"><a href=\"https://postcardstoseattle.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/02/cariboo-mountains-hiking.jpg\"><img src=\"https://postcardstoseattle.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/02/cariboo-mountains-hiking.jpg\" alt=\"cariboo mountains hiking\" class=\"wp-image-6683\"/></a></figure>\n<!-- /wp:image -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>We walked along a&nbsp;river and made it to a beautiful frozen waterfall. It made me think how I’d love to see a timelapse someday of when a waterfall starts to freeze. I loved how quiet it was in the woods and how it felt like we had it to ourselves.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:image {\"id\":6671,\"linkDestination\":\"custom\"} -->\n<figure class=\"wp-block-image\"><a href=\"https://postcardstoseattle.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/02/cariboo-mountains-waterfall.jpg\"><img src=\"https://postcardstoseattle.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/02/cariboo-mountains-waterfall.jpg\" alt=\"cariboo mountains waterfall\" class=\"wp-image-6671\"/></a></figure>\n<!-- /wp:image -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":3} -->\n<h3>CROSS-COUNTRY SKI</h3>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>You can also&nbsp;cross-country ski while staying at Silvertip Lodge. There are plenty of trails to go on that are well-marked, and an easy loop to follow is around the lake. It’s syrprinsingly a hard workout and a great way to see the area.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:image {\"id\":6685,\"linkDestination\":\"custom\"} -->\n<figure class=\"wp-block-image\"><a href=\"https://postcardstoseattle.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/02/cariboo-mountains-skis.jpg\"><img src=\"https://postcardstoseattle.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/02/cariboo-mountains-skis.jpg\" alt=\"cariboo mountains skis\" class=\"wp-image-6685\"/></a></figure>\n<!-- /wp:image -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>One trail I recommend going on is through the old growth forest towards the lake. These trees have been around for hundreds of years and are massive. It was peaceful to snowshoe through the trails here.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:image {\"id\":6672,\"linkDestination\":\"custom\"} -->\n<figure class=\"wp-block-image\"><a href=\"https://postcardstoseattle.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/02/cariboo-mountains-growth-forest.jpg\"><img src=\"https://postcardstoseattle.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/02/cariboo-mountains-growth-forest.jpg\" alt=\"cariboo mountains growth forest\" class=\"wp-image-6672\"/></a></figure>\n<!-- /wp:image -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>While I love winter sports, bringing your own equipment takes up so much space. I loved that I didn’t need to bring any equipment with me to enjoy the different activities. They&nbsp;have a ski shop where you can borrow what you need and even head out on your own for a morning snowshoe if you prefer.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Inside the lodge, they also had plenty of clothes and accessories for sale in case you forgot something. This was extremely convenient, as it’s not like you can just walk to the store in the Cariboo Mountains.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:image {\"id\":6682,\"linkDestination\":\"custom\"} -->\n<figure class=\"wp-block-image\"><a href=\"https://postcardstoseattle.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/02/cariboo-mountains-ski-shop.jpg\"><img src=\"https://postcardstoseattle.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/02/cariboo-mountains-ski-shop.jpg\" alt=\"cariboo mountains ski shop\" class=\"wp-image-6682\"/></a></figure>\n<!-- /wp:image -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Winter is a popular time to visit, there’s plenty to do during the summer too. They’re known for their fishing and they own 14 acres, so you’re sure to catch some fish.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:image {\"id\":6679,\"linkDestination\":\"custom\"} -->\n<figure class=\"wp-block-image\"><a href=\"https://postcardstoseattle.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/02/cariboo-mountains-sunset.jpg\"><img src=\"https://postcardstoseattle.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/02/cariboo-mountains-sunset.jpg\" alt=\"cariboo mountains sunset\" class=\"wp-image-6679\"/></a></figure>\n<!-- /wp:image -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Of course, what would a cold day exploring outside be without ending the day in a hot tub overlooking the lake? They have a small building with a steam room, hot tub, and even a massage room. This was the perfect way to unwind after a long day in the cold.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:image {\"id\":6681,\"linkDestination\":\"custom\"} -->\n<figure class=\"wp-block-image\"><a href=\"https://postcardstoseattle.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/02/cariboo-mountains-hot-tub.jpg\"><img src=\"https://postcardstoseattle.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/02/cariboo-mountains-hot-tub.jpg\" alt=\"cariboo mountains hot tub\" class=\"wp-image-6681\"/></a></figure>\n<!-- /wp:image -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Our days there involved playing outside, eating delicious food, celebrating the day over drinks, sleeping well, and then repeating. My only regret was that I wasn’t there longer. When you have to get on the final helicopter ride to leave Silvertip Lodge, you might shed a tear too.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:image {\"id\":6675,\"linkDestination\":\"custom\"} -->\n<figure class=\"wp-block-image\"><a href=\"https://postcardstoseattle.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/02/cariboo-mountains-silvertip-lodge.jpg\"><img src=\"https://postcardstoseattle.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/02/cariboo-mountains-silvertip-lodge.jpg\" alt=\"cariboo mountains silvertip lodge\" class=\"wp-image-6675\"/></a></figure>\n<!-- /wp:image -->\n\n<!-- wp:separator -->\n<hr class=\"wp-block-separator\"/>\n<!-- /wp:separator -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><em>This post was in partnership with the Cariboo Chilcotin Coast Tourism Association, but all opinions are my own.</em></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->', 'EXPLORING THE WILDERNESS IN THE CARIBOO MOUNTAINS', '', 'inherit', 'closed', 'closed', '', '219-revision-v1', '', '', '2019-04-20 06:03:01', '2019-04-20 06:03:01', '', 219, 'http://localhost/wordpress/2019/04/20/219-revision-v1/', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(227, 1, '2019-04-20 06:05:25', '2019-04-20 06:05:25', '<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>The one place I wanted to go to more than anywhere else in Morocco was Chefchaouen, or “The Blue Pearl.” After not being able to purchase a bus ticket online, I almost missed out on going here by the time I was able to buy it in person (two seats were left!).</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Chefchaouen isn’t a place that you should have an itinerary for. You need to spend several days and just wander around. While the Medina can be confusing at first, it’s quite small compared to places like Marrakech. I also found that more people were willing to point you the correct way if you did get lost (although not everyone would do it for free).</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:image {\"id\":6421,\"linkDestination\":\"custom\"} -->\n<figure class=\"wp-block-image\"><a href=\"https://postcardstoseattle.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/01/visit-chefchaouen-15.jpg\"><img src=\"https://postcardstoseattle.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/01/visit-chefchaouen-15.jpg\" alt=\"visit chefchaouen\" class=\"wp-image-6421\"/></a></figure>\n<!-- /wp:image -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading -->\n<h2>HOW TO GET TO CHEFCHAOUEN</h2>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>This was the most confusing part when I researched it. This magical city isn’t easily accessible, as it’s up north in the Rif Mountains. There are several ways to get here.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><strong>Bus –&nbsp;</strong>This is the most practical and affordable solution. You can book your tickets online at&nbsp;<a href=\"http://www.ctm.ma/\">CTM</a>, but note that if you haven’t bought them within 72 hours of your trip, you’ll need to buy them in person. Here’s how long it will take from these major cities.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><em>Casablanca&nbsp;</em>– 6.5 hours</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><em>Tangier</em>&nbsp;– 45-minute taxi to Tetouan and then 1-hour bus ride</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><em>Fes</em>&nbsp;– 4 hours</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><strong>Train –&nbsp;</strong>There is no train that goes here. However, you can save time and money by taking an overnight train from Marrakech to Tangier. From there you can take the bus or get a taxi.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><strong>Taxi –&nbsp;</strong>This is probably the most expensive option, but if you can find people to split a cab with it’s possible to take a grand taxi to Chefchaouen.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><strong>Fly –&nbsp;</strong>The two closest airports are Tangier and Fes, which you can then take the bus or taxi from.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:image {\"id\":6429,\"linkDestination\":\"custom\"} -->\n<figure class=\"wp-block-image\"><a href=\"https://postcardstoseattle.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/01/visit-chefchaouen-6.jpg\"><img src=\"https://postcardstoseattle.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/01/visit-chefchaouen-6.jpg\" alt=\"visit chefchaouen\" class=\"wp-image-6429\"/></a></figure>\n<!-- /wp:image -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading -->\n<h2>WHERE TO STAY</h2>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>There are many hostels and hotels in Chefchaouen to stay at both in the Medina and outside of it. However, I recommend looking on Air BnB for a really unique experience. I stayed in a five-story house in the middle of the Medina and had it to myself. I felt like a local every morning as I walked around in the middle of everyone setting up their shops for the day. I also had my own rooftop to start the morning each day.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:image {\"id\":6432,\"linkDestination\":\"custom\"} -->\n<figure class=\"wp-block-image\"><a href=\"https://postcardstoseattle.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/01/visit-chefchaouen-4.jpg\"><img src=\"https://postcardstoseattle.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/01/visit-chefchaouen-4.jpg\" alt=\"visit chefchaouen\" class=\"wp-image-6432\"/></a></figure>\n<!-- /wp:image -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading -->\n<h2>WHERE TO EAT</h2>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>There are plenty of places to eat in Chefchaouen, but I recommend staying away from the pizza and Chinese restaurants. Try the local Moroccan food instead! Here were some of my favorite places.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><strong>Sindibad&nbsp;</strong>– For an inexpensive breakfast with a view, go to Sindibad. It has a cozy outdoor seating area and a great view of the city.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:image {\"id\":6427,\"linkDestination\":\"custom\"} -->\n<figure class=\"wp-block-image\"><a href=\"https://postcardstoseattle.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/01/visit-chefchaouen-9.jpg\"><img src=\"https://postcardstoseattle.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/01/visit-chefchaouen-9.jpg\" alt=\"visit chefchaouen\" class=\"wp-image-6427\"/></a></figure>\n<!-- /wp:image -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><strong>Mounir</strong>&nbsp;– Another good place for a cheap breakfast, try the Moroccan pancakes with mint tea.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><strong>Beldi Bab Ssour</strong>&nbsp;– Tucked in a small corner, this is the place where locals come to get lunch (which means you know it’s good). They also have an extensive menu to choose from if you’re getting sick of the same food.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><strong>Casa Aladdin&nbsp;</strong>– This restaurant is a bit more expensive, but it’s the perfect place to watch the sunset from. Get a seat on the terrace and people watch&nbsp;from above. I loved the Moroccan soup and vegetarian tagine.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:image {\"id\":6413,\"linkDestination\":\"custom\"} -->\n<figure class=\"wp-block-image\"><a href=\"https://postcardstoseattle.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/01/visit-chefchaouen-22.jpg\"><img src=\"https://postcardstoseattle.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/01/visit-chefchaouen-22.jpg\" alt=\"visit chefchaouen\" class=\"wp-image-6413\"/></a></figure>\n<!-- /wp:image -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading -->\n<h2>WHAT TO DO</h2>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>As I said before, don’t stick to a strict schedule when you’re visiting Chefchaouen. It’s fun to get lost in the blue streets and see what you’ll discover.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading -->\n<h2>BUY HANDMADE PRODUCTS</h2>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>An advantage a small town like Chefchaouen has is many of the locals actually make the products. In bigger towns, you might find that multiple stores have the same products, meaning they’re probably cheap knockoffs from China. You can also talk to the merchants here to find out more about their goods.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:image {\"id\":6423,\"linkDestination\":\"custom\"} -->\n<figure class=\"wp-block-image\"><a href=\"https://postcardstoseattle.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/01/visit-chefchaouen-13.jpg\"><img src=\"https://postcardstoseattle.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/01/visit-chefchaouen-13.jpg\" alt=\"visit chefchaouen\" class=\"wp-image-6423\"/></a></figure>\n<!-- /wp:image -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading -->\n<h2>HIKE TO THE SPANISH MOSQUE</h2>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>The best way to start your morning is going on a hike up to the mountains. You can watch the sun rise over all of Chefchaouen from here.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading -->\n<h2>SAMPLE SPICES</h2>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>One of my favorite parts of Morocco was all the spices they have and how they’re displayed. Talk to the store owner to see what they all are and sample some before you buy them.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:image {\"id\":6422,\"linkDestination\":\"custom\"} -->\n<figure class=\"wp-block-image\"><a href=\"https://postcardstoseattle.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/01/visit-chefchaouen-14.jpg\"><img src=\"https://postcardstoseattle.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/01/visit-chefchaouen-14.jpg\" alt=\"visit chefchaouen\" class=\"wp-image-6422\"/></a></figure>\n<!-- /wp:image -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading -->\n<h2>RELAX</h2>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Once a day I’d pop into a restaurant, order coffee, and sit on the terrace. Chefchaouen is the perfect place to unwind, and I found I didn’t even want to get on their wi-fi.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:image {\"id\":6428,\"linkDestination\":\"custom\"} -->\n<figure class=\"wp-block-image\"><a href=\"https://postcardstoseattle.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/01/visit-chefchaouen-8.jpg\"><img src=\"https://postcardstoseattle.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/01/visit-chefchaouen-8.jpg\" alt=\"visit chefchaouen\" class=\"wp-image-6428\"/></a></figure>\n<!-- /wp:image -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading -->\n<h2>VISIT THE KASBAH</h2>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Located in the middle of town, this old fortress is now a beautiful garden. For about 50 dirhams you can go inside to explore it.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:image {\"id\":6415,\"linkDestination\":\"custom\"} -->\n<figure class=\"wp-block-image\"><a href=\"https://postcardstoseattle.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/01/visit-chefchaouen-21.jpg\"><img src=\"https://postcardstoseattle.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/01/visit-chefchaouen-21.jpg\" alt=\"visit chefchaouen\" class=\"wp-image-6415\"/></a></figure>\n<!-- /wp:image -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading -->\n<h2>TAKE PLENTY OF PICTURES</h2>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>I’m not a “door person,” but I fell in love with all the doors in Chefchaouen. I kept stopping every few minutes to take pictures of all the beautiful doors in the town.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:image {\"id\":6420,\"linkDestination\":\"custom\"} -->\n<figure class=\"wp-block-image\"><a href=\"https://postcardstoseattle.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/01/visit-chefchaouen-16.jpg\"><img src=\"https://postcardstoseattle.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/01/visit-chefchaouen-16.jpg\" alt=\"visit chefchaouen\" class=\"wp-image-6420\"/></a></figure>\n<!-- /wp:image -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>This is the famous “Instagram street” and is located in the north part of the Medina. Every time I passed this, there were at least half a dozen people waiting to take their picture on it.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:image {\"id\":6418,\"linkDestination\":\"custom\"} -->\n<figure class=\"wp-block-image\"><a href=\"https://postcardstoseattle.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/01/visit-chefchaouen-18.jpg\"><img src=\"https://postcardstoseattle.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/01/visit-chefchaouen-18.jpg\" alt=\"visit chefchaouen\" class=\"wp-image-6418\"/></a></figure>\n<!-- /wp:image -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>As is common in all of Morocco, there are cats everywhere! They looked even more picture-worthy against the blue background of Chefchaouen.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->', 'HOW TO VISIT CHEFCHAOUEN,      MOROCCO’S BLUE CITY', '', 'inherit', 'closed', 'closed', '', '214-revision-v1', '', '', '2019-04-20 06:05:25', '2019-04-20 06:05:25', '', 214, 'http://localhost/wordpress/2019/04/20/214-revision-v1/', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(228, 1, '2019-04-20 06:07:00', '2019-04-20 06:07:00', '<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>The Sahara Desert, also known as “The Great Desert” in Arabic, is the largest hot desert in the world. I’ve seen it in numerous movies and knew even when I was little that one day I needed to go there. As soon as I saw that I could finally go there during my trip to Morocco, I started making plans.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading -->\n<h2>HOW TO GET TO THE SAHARA DESERT</h2>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>There are many different ways to get to the Sahara Desert, but most people head to Merzouga for this. I went with the company Moroccan Bedouin Travel, who picked me up right from my Air BnB in Fes and drove me the entire time through the desert, dropping me off in Marrakech at the end. You can also get picked up from Marrakech if that’s where you’re starting.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>It’s a long drive to the desert no matter which city you’re coming from, so expect to spend at least eight hours on the road the first day. After leaving Fes, we headed into Mid Atlas Mountains, which was a shock to me. I had no idea there were mountains in Morocco, and as we went higher we started to see snow. There was even a hill that had skis at the bottom and monkeys running around in the snow!</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:image {\"id\":6595,\"linkDestination\":\"custom\"} -->\n<figure class=\"wp-block-image\"><a href=\"https://postcardstoseattle.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/02/sahara-desert-4.jpg\"><img src=\"https://postcardstoseattle.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/02/sahara-desert-4-850x567.jpg\" alt=\"sahara desert monkeys\" class=\"wp-image-6595\"/></a></figure>\n<!-- /wp:image -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading -->\n<h2>DRIVING IN THE SAHARA</h2>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>As it became mid-afternoon, I was told we had officially entered the Sahara Desert. This was surprising, as just 10 minutes later we passed through a decent sized town full of restaurants, banks, and cafes. I realized how naive I was in thinking that the Sahara was only full of sand dunes! In fact, the climate reminded me very much of Patagonia at some points, as it was dry but had shrubs growing on the ground.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>We finally reached Merzouga and switched the car for a 4×4 to head out to the camp. If you’ve never driven on sand dunes before, you’re in for a ride. The car was slipping and sliding everywhere, so I completely gave up trying to take a video of the experience.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:image {\"id\":6591,\"linkDestination\":\"custom\"} -->\n<figure class=\"wp-block-image\"><a href=\"https://postcardstoseattle.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/02/camping-sahara-desert-morocco-7.jpg\"><img src=\"https://postcardstoseattle.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/02/camping-sahara-desert-morocco-7-850x567.jpg\" alt=\"camping sahara desert morocco dunes\" class=\"wp-image-6591\"/></a></figure>\n<!-- /wp:image -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading -->\n<h2>CAMPING IN THE DESERT</h2>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>We got to the camp just as it was turning to golden hour, which made the desert seem even more magical. Completely forgetting scorpions call this their home, I kicked my shoes off and started running up the sand dunes to take pictures.&nbsp;I loved sitting on the soft sand and soaking up the scene. You could even see the mountains of Algeria since we were so close to the border.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>I’m not going to lie and say I roughed it camping out in the desert because this was a beautiful luxury camp. The room had a giant king size bed with candles lit, electricity, and running water. The bed was actually the most comfortable one I had the entire time I was in Morocco!</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:image {\"id\":6600,\"linkDestination\":\"custom\"} -->\n<figure class=\"wp-block-image\"><a href=\"https://postcardstoseattle.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/02/camping-sahara-desert-morocco.jpg\"><img src=\"https://postcardstoseattle.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/02/camping-sahara-desert-morocco-850x567.jpg\" alt=\"camping sahara desert morocco tent\" class=\"wp-image-6600\"/></a></figure>\n<!-- /wp:image -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>After I got over how amazing my tent was, I came out to enjoy tea and snacks while the sun set over the mountains. Local music was played by the men who worked at the camp and a fire was started. I heard the desert got cold at night, but I couldn’t believe how drastic the change was just from a few hours earlier when it was hot.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:image {\"id\":6581,\"linkDestination\":\"custom\"} -->\n<figure class=\"wp-block-image\"><a href=\"https://postcardstoseattle.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/02/camping-sahara-desert-5.jpg\"><img src=\"https://postcardstoseattle.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/02/camping-sahara-desert-5-850x567.jpg\" alt=\"camping sahara desert morocco tea\" class=\"wp-image-6581\"/></a></figure>\n<!-- /wp:image -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>For dinner, I went inside a larger tent and had delicious vegetable soup, bread, and tagine for dinner. I went back outside and watched the stars for a bit, reflecting on my trip to Morocco so far. One part I didn’t expect was how dead silent it is in the desert. This makes sense since nothing else is around for miles, but I could actually hear the blood rushing through my head because it was so quiet.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:image {\"id\":6582,\"linkDestination\":\"custom\"} -->\n<figure class=\"wp-block-image\"><a href=\"https://postcardstoseattle.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/02/camping-sahara-desert-6.jpg\"><img src=\"https://postcardstoseattle.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/02/camping-sahara-desert-6-850x567.jpg\" alt=\"camping sahara desert morocco chair\" class=\"wp-image-6582\"/></a></figure>\n<!-- /wp:image -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading -->\n<h2>RIDING A CAMEL</h2>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Besides camping in the desert, something I really wanted to do was ride a camel. To do this, I had to wake up at 6 AM in the cold and complete darkness. I couldn’t see anything but could hear what I thought was a camel off in the distance. I walked towards the sound to find the camel and its handler.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:image {\"id\":6578,\"linkDestination\":\"custom\"} -->\n<figure class=\"wp-block-image\"><a href=\"https://postcardstoseattle.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/02/camping-sahara-desert-2.jpg\"><img src=\"https://postcardstoseattle.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/02/camping-sahara-desert-2-850x567.jpg\" alt=\"camping sahara desert morocco camel dunes\" class=\"wp-image-6578\"/></a></figure>\n<!-- /wp:image -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>If you’ve never been on a camel before, it’s a bit scary when the camel stands up, as you lurch forward. I got used to leaning forward or backward depending on if we were going up or down a dune. The camel stopped at the bottom of one of the higher dunes, and I walked up to get my spot for nature’s show.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:image {\"id\":6597,\"linkDestination\":\"custom\"} -->\n<figure class=\"wp-block-image\"><a href=\"https://postcardstoseattle.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/02/camping-sahara-desert-morocco-4.jpg\"><img src=\"https://postcardstoseattle.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/02/camping-sahara-desert-morocco-4-850x567.jpg\" alt=\"camping sahara desert morocco sunrise\" class=\"wp-image-6597\"/></a></figure>\n<!-- /wp:image -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Orange and pink colors lit up the sky when the sun started rising over the dunes. I spent awhile taking pictures and didn’t want to leave, but I knew I had to get back for breakfast. I said goodbye to my camel friend and headed back to the camp.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:image {\"id\":6599,\"linkDestination\":\"custom\"} -->\n<figure class=\"wp-block-image\"><a href=\"https://postcardstoseattle.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/02/camping-sahara-desert-morocco-6.jpg\"><img src=\"https://postcardstoseattle.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/02/camping-sahara-desert-morocco-6-850x567.jpg\" alt=\"camping sahara desert morocco camel shadow\" class=\"wp-image-6599\"/></a></figure>\n<!-- /wp:image -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Sometimes I get bored easily, but I soaked up every minute at this camp in the Sahara. I love when I’m forced to be offline, away from electronics, and have time to reflect on life. The cushions were so comfortable outside that sometimes I couldn’t believe I was in the desert.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:image {\"id\":6585,\"linkDestination\":\"custom\"} -->\n<figure class=\"wp-block-image\"><a href=\"https://postcardstoseattle.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/02/camping-sahara-desert.jpg\"><img src=\"https://postcardstoseattle.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/02/camping-sahara-desert-850x567.jpg\" alt=\"camping sahara desert morocco breakfast\" class=\"wp-image-6585\"/></a></figure>\n<!-- /wp:image -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>I sadly packed up when it was time to leave and headed back in the 4×4 to the car in Merzouga. I spent several more days with the tour company exploring places like the Road of 1000 Kasbahs and the city of Ouzarette before heading to Marrakech.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>There are many different tour companies that will take you overnight to the desert just for one night, but I highly discourage that. You’ll spend so much time driving that you might not enjoy it as much, and I found the cities within the desert fascinating. I went with Moroccan Bedouin Travel because I was able to spend multiple days exploring the area and had a loose itinerary, so I could spend longer at one place if I wanted to.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Not to sound cliche, but camping in the Sahara Desert is really a once in a lifetime experience, so don’t rush it. You’ll be glad you spent a little more money to have more time exploring this part of Morocco!</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->', 'CAMPING IN THE SAHARA DESERT IN MOROCCO', '', 'inherit', 'closed', 'closed', '', '210-revision-v1', '', '', '2019-04-20 06:07:00', '2019-04-20 06:07:00', '', 210, 'http://localhost/wordpress/2019/04/20/210-revision-v1/', 0, 'revision', '', 0);
INSERT INTO `wp_posts` (`ID`, `post_author`, `post_date`, `post_date_gmt`, `post_content`, `post_title`, `post_excerpt`, `post_status`, `comment_status`, `ping_status`, `post_password`, `post_name`, `to_ping`, `pinged`, `post_modified`, `post_modified_gmt`, `post_content_filtered`, `post_parent`, `guid`, `menu_order`, `post_type`, `post_mime_type`, `comment_count`) VALUES
(229, 1, '2019-04-20 06:10:46', '2019-04-20 06:10:46', '<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Full disclosure: This post contains affiliate links.&nbsp;<strong>?</strong></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>I’ve learned nine languages to conversational level, all as an adult. So I’ve got a good system in place for picking up a new language.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>But when it came to Korean, something was different. Regardless of how many resources I used, I just couldn’t wrap my head around the grammar or the pronunciation. It just didn’t make sense.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>I wondered if it would always be like that. In fact, the first time I learned, I gave up after six months. It was my first language defeat. I wondered if perhaps it and I just weren’t meant to be.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>But a few months later, I realised&nbsp;<a href=\"https://www.fluentin3months.com/korean-in-90-days/\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noreferrer noopener\">I wasn’t ready to give up Korean</a>. I wanted to give it another try.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>I decided to commit to learning Korean as a part of the <em>Add1Challenge</em>, along with using <em>90 Day Korean</em>.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading -->\n<h2 id=\"whatis90daykorean\">What is 90 Day Korean?</h2>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><em>90 Day Korean</em>&nbsp;is a year-long Korean course.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Wait, what?</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Yup, you read that right. It’s a year-long course made up of four 90-day modules that take you from the very basics of Korean through to more advanced Korean lessons.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>In other words, it teaches Korean from the beginning stages to intermediate level.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Essentially,&nbsp;<em>90 Day Korean</em>&nbsp;is an online course, and it goes well beyond what you might expect from a traditional course book. First, each of the lessons includes exercises of some sort to help you master the material you’re studying. The end of each mini module (each of the four main modules contains several one week modules) also includes a mission to help you put everything you learned over the week together.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:image {\"id\":25468,\"align\":\"center\"} -->\n<div class=\"wp-block-image\"><figure class=\"aligncenter\"><img src=\"https://www.fluentin3months.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/02/90day-korean5.png\" alt=\"\" class=\"wp-image-25468\"/></figure></div>\n<!-- /wp:image -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>With&nbsp;<em>90 Day Korean</em>&nbsp;you also have a personal coach who is available to answer your questions, a community forum where you can chat with other Korean learners, and lots of other bonus resources to help you with your Korean.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:image {\"id\":25472,\"align\":\"center\"} -->\n<div class=\"wp-block-image\"><figure class=\"aligncenter\"><img src=\"https://www.fluentin3months.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/02/90day-korean6-1024x494.png\" alt=\"\" class=\"wp-image-25472\"/></figure></div>\n<!-- /wp:image -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>The course is designed so that you can work at your own pace. Even though it’s structured as a 90 day course, you have access to the materials as long as you’re subscribed. You can work through them as you see fit. If you want to learn on the go, you’re covered here, too.&nbsp;<em>90 Day Korean</em>&nbsp;also has an app where you can access the course so that you can take your Korean studies with you wherever you go.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:image {\"id\":25474,\"align\":\"center\"} -->\n<div class=\"wp-block-image\"><figure class=\"aligncenter\"><img src=\"https://www.fluentin3months.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/02/90day-korean1-1024x496.png\" alt=\"\" class=\"wp-image-25474\"/></figure></div>\n<!-- /wp:image -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Each of the four core modules in&nbsp;<em>90 Day Korean</em>&nbsp;consists of 14 smaller modules. Each of these smaller modules includes somewhere between 8-15 lessons for you to complete over the period of a week.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Within each of these smaller modules, you learn:</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:list -->\n<ul><li><em>80/20 Korean Vocabulary</em>&nbsp;– This is the 20% of Korean vocabulary that gives you 80% of the results. To put it another way, the focus is on helping you learn high frequency Korean words that you’ll come across again and again as you learn Korean.</li><li><em>Thematic Korean Lingo</em>&nbsp;– This is about learning Korean words around specific topics like food, shopping, or work</li><li><em>Korean Grammar</em>&nbsp;– taught on an as-needed basis so that you can focus on speaking Korean rather than learning grammar rules. The aim is for you to start communicating in Korean right away</li><li><em>Korean Exercises and Missions</em>&nbsp;– so that you can put everything you’re learning into practice</li><li><em>Cultural Facts</em>&nbsp;– so you’ll understand more of how Korean people think, and what’s important to them.</li><li><em>Grading</em>&nbsp;– when you complete the missions, a native Korean speaker corrects them for you</li></ul>\n<!-- /wp:list -->\n\n<!-- wp:image {\"id\":25469,\"align\":\"center\"} -->\n<div class=\"wp-block-image\"><figure class=\"aligncenter\"><img src=\"https://www.fluentin3months.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/02/90day-korean2-1024x494.png\" alt=\"\" class=\"wp-image-25469\"/></figure></div>\n<!-- /wp:image -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading -->\n<h2 id=\"your1to1koreanlanguagecoach\">Your 1-to-1 Korean Language Coach</h2>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>One of the features that most stood out to me in&nbsp;<em>90 Day Korean</em>&nbsp;is that you’re assigned a 1-to-1 Korean coach. Your coach is there to answer your questions whenever you’re struggling with one of the lessons. You can message them from within the course so that you don’t have to keep track of an email address and they typically respond within 24 hours.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>I sent my coach a few questions as I was studying, asking for tips on pronunciation and irregular verbs and I found their replies not only helpful, but incredibly thorough.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:image {\"id\":25470,\"align\":\"center\"} -->\n<div class=\"wp-block-image\"><figure class=\"aligncenter\"><img src=\"https://www.fluentin3months.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/02/1on1-coach-90day-korean-1024x465.png\" alt=\"\" class=\"wp-image-25470\"/></figure></div>\n<!-- /wp:image -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>When you’re working through a course like this, it’s easy to feel alone and to doubt you’re really understanding everything that you’re learning. That’s where a 1-to-1 coach comes in handy. If ever you’re unsure about whether or not you’ve understood something, or know without a doubt that there’s something you’re not getting, they’re there to help.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading -->\n<h2 id=\"gettingstartedwith90daykorean\">Getting Started with 90 Day Korean</h2>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Even if you have some experience with Korean, I highly recommend starting from the very first module of&nbsp;<em>90 Day Korean</em>.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Why? Because the course not only teaches the Korean language, but also a variety of methods that are proven to help Korean learners pick up the language. The course also walks you through memorization techniques so that the words you learn in the course stick with you.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading -->\n<h2 id=\"myexperienceusing90daykoreanthegood\">My Experience Using 90 Day Korean: The Good</h2>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>When I started&nbsp;<em>90 Day Korean</em>, one thing immediately stood out: the way the course material is written. It’s engaging, well-paced, and best of all, it’s written with a sense of humor. It’s far from dry or boring. The author(s) also weave storytelling into the course, using it to make the grammar and vocabulary you’re learning more relatable and fun.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>This helped me get acquainted with an important part of the Korean language. You see, one of the things that I picked up on when learning both Japanese and Korean is that verb endings are important. Basically, the ending you attach to the verb completely changes its meaning.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>For example, in Korean, 하다 means “to do”. If I want to say “I do”, I would change it to 해요. From there:</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:list -->\n<ul><li>하고 싶어요 – “want to do”</li><li>해 보세요 – “try to do”</li><li>할 수 있어요 – “could do”</li><li>할 수 없어요 – “couldn’t do”</li></ul>\n<!-- /wp:list -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>These endings are key to learning to speak the language, but the first time I tried to learn Korean, I had a hard time finding all the most common verb endings in one place.&nbsp;<em>90 Day Korean</em>&nbsp;turned out to be that place.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>In working through&nbsp;<em>90 Day Korean</em>, I finally had the chance to see all of these different endings in action, read well-written explanations, and do guided practice. It was exactly what I had been looking for in a Korean language resource.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Each of these verb forms are introduced to you gradually as you progress through the course. And despite learning so much useful Korean grammar, the course doesn’t&nbsp;<em>feel</em>grammar intensive. Often, the grammar is masked as a culture lesson, such as when you’re taught to use formal vs informal Korean. At other times, it’s surrounded by lessons focused on vocabulary and other information so you don’t feel as though you’re learning grammar point after grammar point. The lessons are really well organized.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><em>90 Day Korean</em>&nbsp;has several extra features on top of the core course. This includes the option to take notes and store them directly in the course. Personally, I still prefer to take notes by hand. It helps with memory and it’s a pretty rewarding way to see everything you’ve worked on, but it’s still nice to have the option to quickly jot things down and save them for later all in one place.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:image {\"id\":25473,\"align\":\"center\"} -->\n<div class=\"wp-block-image\"><figure class=\"aligncenter\"><img src=\"https://www.fluentin3months.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/02/90-day-korean-1024x768.jpg\" alt=\"\" class=\"wp-image-25473\"/></figure></div>\n<!-- /wp:image -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>You learn a lot of material in&nbsp;<em>90 Day Korean</em>, but as I said before, it’s organized in a way that doesn’t feel overwhelming. It also builds naturally, so everything you learn spans out from what you’ve already studied in earlier lessons.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>I started&nbsp;<em>90 Day Korean</em>&nbsp;a little bit after I began learning Korean for a second time, so I didn’t have a lot of experience with the language.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>I dedicated myself to working through the course at a slightly faster pace than what is recommended. When you sign up for the course, you are sent a new mini module each week, but if you want to work through it a little faster, they have instructions within the course about how to contact them to get “advance access” to the course materials. I took advantage of this and in total, it took me about 4 to 5 months to work through everything at an “accelerated” pace. That said, I still want to go back and spend more time with some of the lessons to make sure I really get the most out of the lesson materials.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>As you work through the course, you can mark what you’ve gone through as complete. This makes the course extremely versatile because you can bounce around from lesson to lesson, focusing on new material and reviewing old material however you see fit.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:image {\"id\":25471,\"align\":\"center\"} -->\n<div class=\"wp-block-image\"><figure class=\"aligncenter\"><img src=\"https://www.fluentin3months.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/02/90day-korean3-1024x493.png\" alt=\"\" class=\"wp-image-25471\"/></figure></div>\n<!-- /wp:image -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":3} -->\n<h3 id=\"learningkoreanwiththe8020rulemaximumresultsminimumeffort\">Learning Korean with the 80/20 Rule: Maximum Results, Minimum Effort</h3>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>In&nbsp;<em>90 Day Korean</em>, what you learn in the course makes use of the Pareto Principle (80/20 rule). Get 80% of the results with 20% of the effort. The material presented in&nbsp;<em>90 Day Korean</em>&nbsp;is curated for you using this approach. You learn the 20% that will do 80% of the work for you.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Here’s an example from the course:</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:quote -->\n<blockquote class=\"wp-block-quote\"><p>“Is there a past tense of -(으)세요?</p><p>“Yes, there is. However, the amount of time you need it compared to the time it takes to learn makes it fall out of the 80/20 category. If you want to learn the most useful Korean as fast as possible, then you’d be better off focusing your time on other parts of the language.”</p></blockquote>\n<!-- /wp:quote -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>When learning a new language, the amount of information that’s thrown at you can feel overwhelming. It’s not hard to wonder: “do I really need to know all of this?”&nbsp;<em>90 Day Korean</em>seeks to eliminate this feeling by eliminating the material you probably don’t need. That way, when you study, you can focus all of your attention on what’s given to you rather than allow yourself to get distracted by that lingering question in the back of your mind.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading -->\n<h2 id=\"myexperienceusing90daykoreanwhatcouldbebetter\">My Experience Using 90 Day Korean: What Could Be Better?</h2>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Each of the lessons in&nbsp;<em>90 Day Korean</em>&nbsp;have fun titles, but when you’re working through the course in a non-linear way, this isn’t very user-friendly. For example, after completing the course, there were a couple of lessons that I wanted to go over again, but because the titles didn’t always tell me what the lesson includes, I had a difficult time finding the particular lessons I was looking for later on.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>While you&nbsp;<em>can</em>&nbsp;access the course from the&nbsp;<em>90 Day Korean</em>&nbsp;app, it isn’t an app version of the course. Instead, you’re simply sent over to your browser when you login and access a mobile-friendly version of the course. The experience is a little different than what you might expect within an app and I found it somewhat distracting.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Finally, I found that the search function within the course didn’t really work. On a couple different occasions, I tried to find lessons using the search function, even once pasting in the exact text I had copied from a lesson. Each time, however, I was given the message that nothing matched my search results. This made it hard to find material I wanted to review.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading -->\n<h2 id=\"myconclusiondoirecommend90daykorean\">My Conclusion: Do I Recommend 90 Day Korean?</h2>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><em>90 Day Korean</em>&nbsp;is an effective way to build a solid foundation in Korean. It includes exercises, lessons, and tools that can aid you in your journey from beginner Korean learner to intermediate level speaker in 12 months or less.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>The materials are put into this course in a way that’s easy to follow and builds on what you’ve previously learned. You don’t need to figure out what to study next and if at any point you ever do feel stuck, your Korean coach is a quick message away. There are also plenty of quizzes and missions to keep the things you’re learning fresh.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->', '90 Day Korean Review: Is 90 Day Korean a Good Course?', '', 'inherit', 'closed', 'closed', '', '202-revision-v1', '', '', '2019-04-20 06:10:46', '2019-04-20 06:10:46', '', 202, 'http://localhost/wordpress/2019/04/20/202-revision-v1/', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(230, 1, '2019-04-20 06:15:25', '2019-04-20 06:15:25', '<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Learning Korean and need a little help getting by? Then you need a great Korean translator app!</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Everyone needs a little help sometimes when learning a new language. It can be difficult starting out if you haven’t met a community of language learners or a language exchange partner to help you make heads or tails of Korean.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>And besides that, it’s always helpful to have an accurate Korean translator on hand when you’re studying on the go. Like when you’re watching a K-Drama on your commute, and want to look up the word for “love triangle” (it’s 삼각관계, <em>samgag gwangye</em>, by the way).</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Having a good English to Korean translator app will help you look up words as you want to learn them and add them to your study list.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Different translators have different purposes, so it can be worth using more than one app. A Korean to English speech translator is handy when a language exchange hits a rough spot. Meanwhile, a text translator helps you when reading Korean articles online.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Korean translators apps all have their pros and cons. Choosing the right one for you is key.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading -->\n<h2 id=\"whattolookforinakoreantranslatorapp\">What to Look for in a Korean Translator App</h2>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>First, you’ll want to take the time to test a few and see if they meet your needs. Are you learning Korean to travel to Korea? Or are you trying to get a deeper knowledge of the language for reading books? Is your primary goal to consume Korean media, or talk to locals?</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Every translator app is different, and they usually focus on one aspect over another. For instance, some translators may only give literal translations. Others may translate idioms and colloquial phrases accurately. This is important to note because you may want to say something that doesn’t have a natural translation in Korean. For example, of you look up “a piece of cake,” then a literal translation will pull up 케이크 조각 (<em>keikeu jogag</em>), which means “cake piece.” What you actually wanted to say was “it was easy,” and that’s 식은 죽 먹기 (<em>sig-eun jug meoggi</em>) which in Korean is the idiom “like eating cold porridge.”</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>You need to ask yourself: are you translating from speech or text most? Are you looking for something that needs some basic knowledge of Korean to make it useful? Or are you a beginner and need something that simplifies it – even helping you read&nbsp;<em>Hangul</em>, the Korean script?</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Once you decide how you’ll be using the app, you can find one that meets your needs.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading -->\n<h2 id=\"onemajorcaveatavoidtranslatorappdependence\">One Major Caveat: Avoid Translator App Dependence!</h2>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Sure, Korean translator apps can be super helpful if you use them right. But they can also be one of the reasons you don’t succeed in learning Korean.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>It can be too easy to rely on translator apps, especially because of their convenience. At first, you’re only looking up words you don’t know to help you flesh out a sentence. But then you’re using it to check the accuracy of your whole sentence. And then you use it to help you create the whole sentence for you.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>This “translator trap” is a major pitfall for language learners. It takes away the mental stimulation of&nbsp;<em>trying to remember the language on your own</em>. If you become this reliant on translators, then you may be better deleting them from your phone and sticking with a real-life dictionary — yes, I mean a physical book. If you really want to know something, you’ll have to put in the effort to flip through the book and find it. And it won’t always be handy. This will limit how much you look up, and push you to remember on your own and create sentences without help.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>With that said, let’s look at some of the best Korean translator apps.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading -->\n<h2 id=\"7bestkoreantranslatorapps\">7 Best Korean Translator Apps</h2>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":3} -->\n<h3 id=\"1naverkoreandictionary\">1. Naver Korean Dictionary</h3>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><strong>For&nbsp;<a href=\"https://itunes.apple.com/us/app/naver-korean-dictionary/id673085116?mt=8\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noreferrer noopener\">iOS</a>,&nbsp;<a href=\"https://play.google.com/store/apps/details?id=com.nhn.android.naverdic&amp;hl=en\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noreferrer noopener\">Android</a>&nbsp;and&nbsp;<a href=\"https://endic.naver.com/?sLn=en\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noreferrer noopener\">web browser</a>.</strong></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>The golden Korean dictionary and translator. When you search for a translation, it pops up with tons of variations and sentences to help you learn its usage. And the homepage features daily Korean conversations to practice your listening skills, as well as idioms, grammar tips, and words-of-the-day. As far as a translator goes,&nbsp;<em>Naver</em>&nbsp;does the best job of combining translation and learning.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>There’s also the original&nbsp;<em>Naver</em>&nbsp;app all in Korean, with a search function that allows you to find info Wikipedia-style. It’s language-immersive and includes news and stories in Korean. But, because it’s all in Korean, it’s best for advanced learners.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><strong>Pros:</strong></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:list -->\n<ul><li>Best for those who have at least a&nbsp;<em>little</em>&nbsp;knowledge of the language</li><li>Better for in-depth knowledge and context of word usage</li><li>Includes accurate sample sentences and alternate phrases with every translation</li><li>Features daily tips, grammar, idioms, and more to boost your learning</li><li>Includes audio for translations, as well as Korean conversations to practice listening skills</li></ul>\n<!-- /wp:list -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><strong>Cons:</strong></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:list -->\n<ul><li>Because only written out on dictionary pages, you must be able to read Hangul comfortably to benefit from it.</li><li>While this translator has a&nbsp;<em>ton</em>&nbsp;to offer to aid learning, it also provides so many sample sentences, it may become easy to cheat your way through creating your own sentences</li></ul>\n<!-- /wp:list -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":3} -->\n<h3 id=\"2papagotranslate\">2. Papago Translate</h3>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><strong>For&nbsp;<a href=\"https://itunes.apple.com/us/app/naver-papago-translate/id1147874819?mt=8\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noreferrer noopener\">iOS</a>,&nbsp;<a href=\"https://play.google.com/store/apps/details?id=com.naver.labs.translator&amp;hl=en\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noreferrer noopener\">Android</a>&nbsp;and&nbsp;<a href=\"https://chrome.google.com/webstore/detail/papago-translate/enddgifdbfoefnelepppgaabobdfbcpe?hl=en\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noreferrer noopener\">Google Chrome</a>.</strong></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Also created by&nbsp;<em>Naver</em>, this is the true translator versus a dictionary. Even though this is like a “lite” version of&nbsp;<em>Naver</em>, it has its differences… and they’re fantastic. For one, the interface is smooth and simple. You can quickly select your languages and input method: typing, microphone, conversation, or text recognition with your camera.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Plus, it includes a place for you to save your words to “Favorites” to create a word and phrase bank to practice. It saves your history, so you won’t forget what you looked up or part of your conversation. And, it has two features that will be amazing aids for beginners and travelers: a phrasebook and website translator.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>One thing I was very impressed with was the Kids section. If you want to include your child in on your Korean studies, the app has cute, colorful picture cards on various topics in Korean and English.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><strong>Pros:</strong></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:list -->\n<ul><li>Best for beginners, travelers, and for quick, on-the-go translating help</li><li>Simple, easy interface and kid-friendly</li><li>Website translation and quick phrasebook, sorted by topic</li><li>Saved words and history for easy review</li><li>Includes&nbsp;<em>Papago Mini</em>, which hovers over your other apps for quicker translation on screen</li></ul>\n<!-- /wp:list -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><strong>Cons:</strong></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:list -->\n<ul><li>Like the&nbsp;<em>Nave</em>r translator, it doesn’t include romanization, so knowing Hangul is a must</li><li>It doesn’t provide sample sentences or context. You get the word-for-word translation</li></ul>\n<!-- /wp:list -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":3} -->\n<h3 id=\"3googletranslate\">3. Google Translate</h3>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><strong>For&nbsp;<a href=\"https://itunes.apple.com/gb/app/google-translate/id414706506?mt=8\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noreferrer noopener\">iOS</a>,&nbsp;<a href=\"https://play.google.com/store/apps/details?id=com.google.android.apps.translate&amp;hl=en_GB\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noreferrer noopener\">Android</a>&nbsp;and&nbsp;<a href=\"https://translate.google.com/\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noreferrer noopener\">web browser</a>.</strong></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Of course, this had to be on the list. The most well-known translator app has come a long way in recent years. With verified translations and various ways to input, it’s a tried-and-true favorite.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>But,&nbsp;<em>Google Translate</em>&nbsp;isn’t perfect. It’s multilingual, unlike some others that focus on excelling&nbsp;<em>only</em>&nbsp;at translating Korean. Asian languages often differ drastically in speech. Many phrases don’t translate well through&nbsp;<em>Google</em>&nbsp;because it wouldn’t be said that way in Korean at all. Without some basic knowledge of how the language functions grammatically, it’s easy to get a bad translation.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>That said, if you have a basic understanding of Korean – enough to catch where grammar might be off, or when something may sound more natural –&nbsp;<em>Google Translate</em>&nbsp;can be a helpful resource.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->', 'The 7 Best Korean Translator Apps for Korean Learners', '', 'inherit', 'closed', 'closed', '', '198-revision-v1', '', '', '2019-04-20 06:15:25', '2019-04-20 06:15:25', '', 198, 'http://localhost/wordpress/2019/04/20/198-revision-v1/', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(231, 1, '2019-04-20 06:16:16', '2019-04-20 06:16:16', '<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>If you really dream of traveling more, then get ready to have all your excuses removed.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Too many times I hear, “I wish I could travel more, but I can’t afford it.”</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>The thing is, I haven’t heard this common excuse from a homeless person or someone who has been out of work for years. I would really believe it in those case. Instead I hear it multiple times a year from people who earn more money than I do. Or from teachers who have the whole summer off and yet they just stay home.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Usually what’s holding them back is a misunderstanding of how inexpensive travel can be. Or it boils down to just not having their priorities straight.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Or both.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>If you want to travel more, it’s not hard to find a way. But if it’s #7 on your list behind the latest iPhone, new cars, a bigger house, weekly clothes shopping, a Starbucks addiction, and your three pets then yeah, that makes it harder.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Traveling more doesn’t require winning the lottery, but if you’re not loaded with extra cash, it does require a little effort and some contrarian thinking. Here’s what to do if you want to travel more and are willing to do a little work to make it happen.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Table of Contents</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:list -->\n<ul><li><a href=\"https://www.cheapestdestinationsblog.com/2019/04/14/6-ways-travel-more-current-income/#1_Game_the_Loyalty_Programs_Sign-up_Bonuses\">1. Game the Loyalty Programs: Sign-up Bonuses</a></li><li><a href=\"https://www.cheapestdestinationsblog.com/2019/04/14/6-ways-travel-more-current-income/#2_Game_the_Loyalty_Systems_2_Leverage_Your_Spending\">2. Game the Loyalty Systems 2: Leverage Your Spending</a></li><li><a href=\"https://www.cheapestdestinationsblog.com/2019/04/14/6-ways-travel-more-current-income/#3_Be_Spontaneous_With_Your_Travel\">3. Be Spontaneous With Your Travel</a></li><li><a href=\"https://www.cheapestdestinationsblog.com/2019/04/14/6-ways-travel-more-current-income/#4_Extend_Business_Trips\">4. Extend Business Trips</a></li><li><a href=\"https://www.cheapestdestinationsblog.com/2019/04/14/6-ways-travel-more-current-income/#5_Go_for_Local_Adventures_Nearby\">5. Go for Local Adventures Nearby</a></li><li><a href=\"https://www.cheapestdestinationsblog.com/2019/04/14/6-ways-travel-more-current-income/#6_Live_Abroad_to_Travel_More\">6. Live Abroad to Travel More</a></li></ul>\n<!-- /wp:list -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":3} -->\n<h3>1. Game the Loyalty Programs: Sign-up Bonuses</h3>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>If your personal credit is good enough to get an average credit card, then don’t get an&nbsp;<em>average</em>&nbsp;credit card. Get one that will really reward you in a big way for your spending–starting with a good sign-up bonus. I once got four free international flights in the course of one year by playing this game, to destinations as far away as Chile and Thailand.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>For instance, you can go sign up for a&nbsp;<a href=\"https://www.referyourchasecard.com/223/T1BJJCR7PU\">Southwest Airlines card</a>&nbsp;right now and spend $1,000 on it, you’ll get 40,000 points in their rewards program. That’s enough for a $400 plane ticket. You can go most anywhere in the USA for that, and often Mexico or&nbsp;<a href=\"https://www.luxurylatinamerica.com/belize.html\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noreferrer noopener\">Belize</a>.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Assuming you’ve got good enough credit to apply for multiple cards, you can play several angles to cover the main costs of your vacation.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>A) Start with one airline card, preferably for the airline where you already have the most miles or the one you’re probably going to fly on the most over the next year or two. If you live somewhere with lots of competition and won’t use the card internationally, then just see who is offering a good sign-up incentive. Usually you’ll get between 30,000 and 60,000 miles. If you sign up for the&nbsp;<a href=\"https://www.referyourchasecard.com/217/5LFBBVJ92X\">United Explorer Mileage Plus card</a>&nbsp;right now you can get 40,000 miles. You have to spend $2,000 on the card in 90 days, so plan on putting some big purchases on it (which also earn points). That many miles will get you to Canada, Mexico, or Central America just on the bonus—or across the USA.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Then do it again for another airline to bank miles for different locations. Delta is offering a 60,000 mile sign-up bonus for their&nbsp;<a href=\"http://refer.amex.us/TIMOtLzVmG?xl=cpqa\">Gold Delta SkyMiles Card</a>. With all of these you can use the miles to book with their partner airlines, so those 60,000 miles can really open up the world. Following that referral link though; if you just pull it up on Google they’re only offering 30,000.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>B) Then get a credit card that’s tied to a specific hotel chain. You’ll usually get the best sign-up bonus from the IHG one (Intercontinental, Holiday Inn, Kimpton) from Chase or the Club Carlson (Radisson) one from US Bank. Right now the&nbsp;<a href=\"https://www.referyourchasecard.com/251/VGRJUWTOTN\">IHG Rewards Club Premier card</a>&nbsp;gives you a sign-up bonus of 80,000 points after spending $2,000, Platinum status (free room upgrades) and a free night when you renew the card in a year.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>After you get the bonus, you’ll have several free hotel nights. Marriott is currently offering a 100,000 points deal, but it’s not apples to apples with hotel loyalty program points needed. In my experience, you’ll get more free nights with 80K from IHG than you will 100K from Marriott or Hyatt. As always though, a hotel chain you use a lot is going to make more sense than one you seldom stay with.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>C) Get a credit card (or use one that you already have) that allows you to contribute miles to multiple programs and top off your accounts. American Express has the Membership Rewards program, but better bets these days are Chase Sapphire and Barclay Arrival Plus, which have a more useful array of programs and offer more bonus earning opportunites. Also, they don’t levy a foreign transaction fee, which some Amex cards still annoyingly do.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>With these cards you can transfer over just the points you need for a ticket, as I did last week with Delta to “buy” my wife a ticket to come with me to Montana later this year.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":3} -->\n<h3>2. Game the Loyalty Systems 2: Leverage Your Spending</h3>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Once you have one or more of these cards, use them for as much of your spending as possible that you’re going to be able to pay off. Every dollar you spend each month on cable, internet, phone bills, gas, Uber/Lyft, or public transportation could be putting more points on your balance. Then there are all kinds of bonus earning opportunities from mileage malls, dining programs, and using the card for purchases at that airline or hotel chain. Add up what you spend in a typical year that you could put on a card and it’s probably enough to earn another flight or couple hotel nights.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Some people get rid of a card after a year or two because they mainly got it for the sign-up bonus. If you get lots of perks from your card though, like upgraded status or free checked bags, it’s usually worth it to keep paying the annual fee and rack up miles from your spending. I have cards for four airlines. This way I avoid the bag fees that put me in a bad mood and I never purchase a flight without earning bonus miles.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>There may be spending discount promotions too. In three different countries I’ve gotten a night at a Holiday Inn or Holiday Inn Express where I wanted to go for just 5,000 points because the place was one their “points breaks” listings at a huge discount. I’ve gotten several Hilton rooms for 10,000 points. I once flew from Mexico to Peru and back for just 20,000 airline miles on United (actually flying on Avianca) because of a discounted miles promotion they were running for United Chase credit card holders.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":3} -->\n<h3>3. Be Spontaneous With Your Travel</h3>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Sometimes taking advantage of these great deals means doing things in the opposite order of most people. Instead of deciding where to go and then figuring out how to jam that place into your budget, save the destination choice for last. If you can use miles and hotel points in Place D but not in A, B, or C, then go directly to D!</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Or use a site that specializes in last-minute deals and just see what pops up. Examples in all budget ranges include LuxuryLink, Groupon, Jetsetter, Hotwire, CheapCaribbean.com, and now most of the big online travel agents like Priceline.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Or throw it wide open: go to Google Flights, put in your home airport, and see what comes up. If you’re thinking you can’t get a summer vacation deal from NYC, think again. You just need to be flexible. Granted, I only found one flight under $600 to Europe then (Madrid), but there are plenty of deals in this hemisphere in mid-June for a week:</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:image {\"id\":13582,\"align\":\"center\"} -->\n<div class=\"wp-block-image\"><figure class=\"aligncenter\"><img src=\"https://www.cheapestdestinationsblog.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/12/google-flights-summer.jpg\" alt=\"Find the best vacation flight deals from your own airport\" class=\"wp-image-13582\"/></figure></div>\n<!-- /wp:image -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Go check from your own city, but here are the round-trip price highlights from that screen shot above: Atlanta $135, Miami $207, Mexico City $309. If I could fit it on here, you’d see some South America destinations for less than $500 and some Canadian ones less than $200.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>You can do something similar with the&nbsp;<a href=\"http://www.kqzyfj.com/click-1222312-12532523\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noreferrer noopener\">Skyscanner</a>&nbsp;app or website, just putting in your home airport and picking “anywhere” for the destination. Haven’t heard of the place before? So what. You can learn most everything you need to know about it in one day online, or just buy a guidebook right before you take off and read it on the plane. You’ll probably have a better time than you did on any previous long-planned vacation because there were fun surprises.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Don’t forget about regional flight options either. You can pick up some surprisingly cheap flights within Asia or Europe, or with one of the many&nbsp;<a href=\"https://www.cheapestdestinationsblog.com/2017/01/25/the-budget-airlines-of-mexico/\">Mexican airlines</a>. There are great deals in the USA with&nbsp;<a href=\"https://www.cheapestdestinationsblog.com/2017/01/30/flying-on-allegiant-air-without-baggage-fees-take-2/\">Allegiant</a>&nbsp;if you’re traveling light.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":3} -->\n<h3>4. Extend Business Trips</h3>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Many people travel hours away from their home city, then don’t see much beyond a hotel, offices, or a convention center. This is a big missed opportunity. Make it a&nbsp;<a href=\"https://blog.bonwi.com/traveling-for-business-or-pleasure-why-not-both/\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noreferrer noopener\">bleisure trip</a>instead.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>When I worked in a corporate job, here are just a few places I traveled on my own over a long weekend: Montreal, Austin, San Francisco, D.C., Dallas, San Jose, Boston, Las Vegas… In all these cases, there was some biz meeting or convention I had to go to, but I always booked my flight back a few days later whenever possible. As long as the price was the same or less (it usually was because I stayed over a Saturday), then they couldn’t have cared less. All I had to pay for was a couple days of local expenses. Could you do the same but you just don’t?</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>When I travel through airports on Fridays, they’re always packed wall to wall with people in business clothing coming home from their work on the road. A lot of them have families with kids I’m sure and need to get back for the soccer match or swim meet. But if you don’t, what’s your hurry?</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:image {\"id\":13583} -->\n<figure class=\"wp-block-image\"><img src=\"https://www.cheapestdestinationsblog.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/12/saint-augustine-top-600x385.jpg\" alt=\"St. Augustine from Orlando \" class=\"wp-image-13583\"/></figure>\n<!-- /wp:image -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><em>A couple hours from Orlando…</em></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Sure, Orlando might not be your scene, but you can&nbsp;<a href=\"https://blog.bonwi.com/5-best-florida-beaches-easily-reached-orlando/\">reach beaches on either coast</a>&nbsp;in a rental care in two hours. Or you could head to&nbsp;<a href=\"https://www.perceptivetravel.com/issues/0319/usa.html\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noreferrer noopener\">St. Augustine</a>. If you’re&nbsp;<a href=\"http://www.perceptivetravel.com/issues/0412/las_vegas.html\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noreferrer noopener\">in Vegas</a>&nbsp;and don’t like to gamble, there are a lot of cool things to see and do within driving distance, including the Grand Canyon. Almost anywhere can be a fun adventure or at least a good springboard to one.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":3} -->\n<h3>5. Go for Local Adventures Nearby</h3>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>When I lived in Nashville I had great vacations in Memphis,&nbsp;<a href=\"http://www.perceptivetravel.com/issues/0812/kentucky.html\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noreferrer noopener\">Lexington</a>, Chattanooga,&nbsp;<a href=\"http://www.gonomad.com/2401-a-family-fun-blast-off-in-huntsville-alabama\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noreferrer noopener\">Huntsville</a>, the&nbsp;<a href=\"https://www.cheapestdestinationsblog.com/2009/03/25/i-found-your-lost-luggage/\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noreferrer noopener\">Unclaimed Baggage Center</a>, Birmingham, and some state parks. I can think of a year’s worth of cool weekend trips worth taking from where I grew up in Virginia. When I lived in Tampa, I discovered&nbsp;<a href=\"https://perceptivetravel.com/blog/2017/01/29/main-street-usa-deland-florida/\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noreferrer noopener\">Deland</a>&nbsp;and&nbsp;<a href=\"https://perceptivetravel.com/blog/2018/02/08/thomas-edison-henry-ford-estate-fort-myers/\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noreferrer noopener\">Fort Myers</a>, took a trip to the&nbsp;<a href=\"https://www.perceptivetravel.com/issues/0718/florida.html\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noreferrer noopener\">Florida Keys</a>,&nbsp;<a href=\"https://www.perceptivetravel.com/issues/0418/florida.html\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noreferrer noopener\">kayaked the Calusa Blueway</a>, and went tubing down a spring-fed river–all without ever getting on a plane.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>There are probably at least 20 places worth visiting within three hours of your home that you’ve never been to, but have some vague intention of visiting someday. There are probably 20 or 30 more that just haven’t gotten onto your radar. Then there are the ones that may not be all that notable, but are probably still going to be an adventure.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Take the commuter train to the end of the line. Pick a town on the map and drive there. Get a local book on strange things to see in your state and start visiting them.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":3} -->\n<h3>6. Live Abroad to Travel More</h3>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>You want to&nbsp;<em>really</em>&nbsp;expand your travel options? Move somewhere that’s already foreign. Then everywhere you go will be exciting.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>From where I live now in central Mexico, I can take a direct bus to a few dozen destinations and all of them are going to feel exotic. Who’s ever heard of&nbsp;<a href=\"https://www.cheapestdestinationsblog.com/2014/04/29/a-great-backpacker-town-with-no-backpackers-cuetzalan-mexico/\">Cuetzalan</a>&nbsp;or&nbsp;<a href=\"https://www.cheapestdestinationsblog.com/2011/01/06/zacatecas-just-another-incredible-mexican-city-with-almost-no-foreign-tourists/\">Zacatecas</a>? When my wife and I taught English for a year in Korea, we went all over the country, to strange places like Maisan and not-so-strange ones like Cheju Island that still felt very out of the ordinary to us foreigners.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:image {\"id\":7772,\"align\":\"center\"} -->\n<div class=\"wp-block-image\"><figure class=\"aligncenter\"><img src=\"https://www.cheapestdestinationsblog.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/12/maisan.jpg\" alt=\"maisan Korea\" class=\"wp-image-7772\"/></figure></div>\n<!-- /wp:image -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>If you already&nbsp;<a href=\"https://www.cheapestdestinationsblog.com/2018/03/08/how-much-does-it-cost-to-live-in-hungary/\">live in Budapest</a>, you don’t have to pay $1,200 to go somewhere in Europe. If you already live in Malaysia, you can just hop on a bus or train to get to Singapore or Thailand. Not only are you already living&nbsp;<a href=\"http://www.cheaplivingabroad.com/packages/\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noreferrer noopener\">a better life for half the price</a>, you can now travel to foreign lands without flying across an ocean to do so.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>If you follow just one or two of the tips in this article, you will take more vacations without spending more money. You can stop saying “<a href=\"https://www.cheapestdestinationsblog.com/2016/05/18/i-wish-i-could-travel-more/\">I wish I could travel more</a>” for good. Instead your challenge—if you’re an American working stiff—will be getting enough vacation time instead.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><strong>Save</strong></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->', '6 Ways to Travel More on Your Current Income', '', 'inherit', 'closed', 'closed', '', '186-revision-v1', '', '', '2019-04-20 06:16:16', '2019-04-20 06:16:16', '', 186, 'http://localhost/wordpress/2019/04/20/186-revision-v1/', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
