(252, 1, '2019-04-21 03:49:27', '2019-04-21 03:49:27', '<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>The Sahara Desert, also known as “The Great Desert” in Arabic, is the largest hot desert in the world. I’ve seen it in numerous movies and knew even when I was little that one day I needed to go there. As soon as I saw that I could finally go there during my trip to Morocco, I started making plans.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading -->\n<h2>HOW TO GET TO THE SAHARA DESERT</h2>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>There are many different ways to get to the Sahara Desert, but most people head to Merzouga for this. I went with the company Moroccan Bedouin Travel, who picked me up right from my Air BnB in Fes and drove me the entire time through the desert, dropping me off in Marrakech at the end. You can also get picked up from Marrakech if that’s where you’re starting.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>It’s a long drive to the desert no matter which city you’re coming from, so expect to spend at least eight hours on the road the first day. After leaving Fes, we headed into Mid Atlas Mountains, which was a shock to me. I had no idea there were mountains in Morocco, and as we went higher we started to see snow. There was even a hill that had skis at the bottom and monkeys running around in the snow!</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:image {\"id\":6595,\"linkDestination\":\"custom\"} -->\n<figure class=\"wp-block-image\"><a href=\"https://postcardstoseattle.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/02/sahara-desert-4.jpg\"><img src=\"https://postcardstoseattle.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/02/sahara-desert-4-850x567.jpg\" alt=\"sahara desert monkeys\" class=\"wp-image-6595\"/></a></figure>\n<!-- /wp:image -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading -->\n<h2>DRIVING IN THE SAHARA</h2>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>As it became mid-afternoon, I was told we had officially entered the Sahara Desert. This was surprising, as just 10 minutes later we passed through a decent sized town full of restaurants, banks, and cafes. I realized how naive I was in thinking that the Sahara was only full of sand dunes! In fact, the climate reminded me very much of Patagonia at some points, as it was dry but had shrubs growing on the ground.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>We finally reached Merzouga and switched the car for a 4×4 to head out to the camp. If you’ve never driven on sand dunes before, you’re in for a ride. The car was slipping and sliding everywhere, so I completely gave up trying to take a video of the experience.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:image {\"id\":6591,\"linkDestination\":\"custom\"} -->\n<figure class=\"wp-block-image\"><a href=\"https://postcardstoseattle.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/02/camping-sahara-desert-morocco-7.jpg\"><img src=\"https://postcardstoseattle.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/02/camping-sahara-desert-morocco-7-850x567.jpg\" alt=\"camping sahara desert morocco dunes\" class=\"wp-image-6591\"/></a></figure>\n<!-- /wp:image -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading -->\n<h2>CAMPING IN THE DESERT</h2>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>We got to the camp just as it was turning to golden hour, which made the desert seem even more magical. Completely forgetting scorpions call this their home, I kicked my shoes off and started running up the sand dunes to take pictures.&nbsp;I loved sitting on the soft sand and soaking up the scene. You could even see the mountains of Algeria since we were so close to the border.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>I’m not going to lie and say I roughed it camping out in the desert because this was a beautiful luxury camp. The room had a giant king size bed with candles lit, electricity, and running water. The bed was actually the most comfortable one I had the entire time I was in Morocco!</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:image {\"id\":6600,\"linkDestination\":\"custom\"} -->\n<figure class=\"wp-block-image\"><a href=\"https://postcardstoseattle.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/02/camping-sahara-desert-morocco.jpg\"><img src=\"https://postcardstoseattle.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/02/camping-sahara-desert-morocco-850x567.jpg\" alt=\"camping sahara desert morocco tent\" class=\"wp-image-6600\"/></a></figure>\n<!-- /wp:image -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>After I got over how amazing my tent was, I came out to enjoy tea and snacks while the sun set over the mountains. Local music was played by the men who worked at the camp and a fire was started. I heard the desert got cold at night, but I couldn’t believe how drastic the change was just from a few hours earlier when it was hot.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:image {\"id\":6581,\"linkDestination\":\"custom\"} -->\n<figure class=\"wp-block-image\"><a href=\"https://postcardstoseattle.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/02/camping-sahara-desert-5.jpg\"><img src=\"https://postcardstoseattle.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/02/camping-sahara-desert-5-850x567.jpg\" alt=\"camping sahara desert morocco tea\" class=\"wp-image-6581\"/></a></figure>\n<!-- /wp:image -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>For dinner, I went inside a larger tent and had delicious vegetable soup, bread, and tagine for dinner. I went back outside and watched the stars for a bit, reflecting on my trip to Morocco so far. One part I didn’t expect was how dead silent it is in the desert. This makes sense since nothing else is around for miles, but I could actually hear the blood rushing through my head because it was so quiet.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:image {\"id\":6582,\"linkDestination\":\"custom\"} -->\n<figure class=\"wp-block-image\"><a href=\"https://postcardstoseattle.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/02/camping-sahara-desert-6.jpg\"><img src=\"https://postcardstoseattle.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/02/camping-sahara-desert-6-850x567.jpg\" alt=\"camping sahara desert morocco chair\" class=\"wp-image-6582\"/></a></figure>\n<!-- /wp:image -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading -->\n<h2>RIDING A CAMEL</h2>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Besides camping in the desert, something I really wanted to do was ride a camel. To do this, I had to wake up at 6 AM in the cold and complete darkness. I couldn’t see anything but could hear what I thought was a camel off in the distance. I walked towards the sound to find the camel and its handler.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:image {\"id\":6578,\"linkDestination\":\"custom\"} -->\n<figure class=\"wp-block-image\"><a href=\"https://postcardstoseattle.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/02/camping-sahara-desert-2.jpg\"><img src=\"https://postcardstoseattle.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/02/camping-sahara-desert-2-850x567.jpg\" alt=\"camping sahara desert morocco camel dunes\" class=\"wp-image-6578\"/></a></figure>\n<!-- /wp:image -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>If you’ve never been on a camel before, it’s a bit scary when the camel stands up, as you lurch forward. I got used to leaning forward or backward depending on if we were going up or down a dune. The camel stopped at the bottom of one of the higher dunes, and I walked up to get my spot for nature’s show.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:image {\"id\":6597,\"linkDestination\":\"custom\"} -->\n<figure class=\"wp-block-image\"><a href=\"https://postcardstoseattle.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/02/camping-sahara-desert-morocco-4.jpg\"><img src=\"https://postcardstoseattle.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/02/camping-sahara-desert-morocco-4-850x567.jpg\" alt=\"camping sahara desert morocco sunrise\" class=\"wp-image-6597\"/></a></figure>\n<!-- /wp:image -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Orange and pink colors lit up the sky when the sun started rising over the dunes. I spent awhile taking pictures and didn’t want to leave, but I knew I had to get back for breakfast. I said goodbye to my camel friend and headed back to the camp.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:image {\"id\":6599,\"linkDestination\":\"custom\"} -->\n<figure class=\"wp-block-image\"><a href=\"https://postcardstoseattle.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/02/camping-sahara-desert-morocco-6.jpg\"><img src=\"https://postcardstoseattle.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/02/camping-sahara-desert-morocco-6-850x567.jpg\" alt=\"camping sahara desert morocco camel shadow\" class=\"wp-image-6599\"/></a></figure>\n<!-- /wp:image -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Sometimes I get bored easily, but I soaked up every minute at this camp in the Sahara. I love when I’m forced to be offline, away from electronics, and have time to reflect on life. The cushions were so comfortable outside that sometimes I couldn’t believe I was in the desert.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:image {\"id\":6585,\"linkDestination\":\"custom\"} -->\n<figure class=\"wp-block-image\"><a href=\"https://postcardstoseattle.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/02/camping-sahara-desert.jpg\"><img src=\"https://postcardstoseattle.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/02/camping-sahara-desert-850x567.jpg\" alt=\"camping sahara desert morocco breakfast\" class=\"wp-image-6585\"/></a></figure>\n<!-- /wp:image -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>I sadly packed up when it was time to leave and headed back in the 4×4 to the car in Merzouga. I spent several more days with the tour company exploring places like the Road of 1000 Kasbahs and the city of Ouzarette before heading to Marrakech.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>There are many different tour companies that will take you overnight to the desert just for one night, but I highly discourage that. You’ll spend so much time driving that you might not enjoy it as much, and I found the cities within the desert fascinating. I went with&nbsp;Moroccan Bedouin Travel&nbsp;because I was able to spend multiple days exploring the area and had a loose itinerary, so I could spend longer at one place if I wanted to.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Not to sound cliche, but camping in the Sahara Desert is really a once in a lifetime experience, so don’t rush it. You’ll be glad you spent a little more money to have more time exploring this part of Morocco!</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->', 'CAMPING IN THE SAHARA DESERT IN MOROCCO', '', 'inherit', 'closed', 'closed', '', '210-revision-v1', '', '', '2019-04-21 03:49:27', '2019-04-21 03:49:27', '', 210, 'http://localhost/wordpress/2019/04/21/210-revision-v1/', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
