(257, 1, '2019-04-21 04:12:29', '2019-04-21 04:12:29', '<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>One of the most beautiful cities in all of Europe, Milan has been visited by tourists for centuries. Practically swimming with art, culture, and history, spending one day in Milan is a time well-spent. When you’re planning what to do in Milan, don’t forget about the amazing landmarks of the city, many of which are easy to spot as you walk around.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Table of Contents</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:list -->\n<ul><li>Best Time to Visit Milan</li><li>Milan Transportation</li><li>What to Do in One Day in Milan</li><li>Where to Eat in Milan</li><li>Where to Stay in Milan</li><li>Day Trips from Milan</li></ul>\n<!-- /wp:list -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading -->\n<h2>BEST TIME TO VISIT MILAN</h2>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Generally, there is no best time to visit Milan, as it’s great to visit any time of the year. If you’re looking to have a more peaceful time and to avoid many of the tourists, then&nbsp;<strong>April to May</strong>&nbsp;are ideal months. The same is true for&nbsp;<strong>September and October</strong>&nbsp;as well.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>On the other hand, if you want to have the full tourist experience, then the summer months are ideal for that. The climate in Milan is quite warm, and the weather is normally great. Due to this, it’s no wonder that summer in Milan is the height of the tourist season. There is no specific season for fashion shopping, though, since it’s one of the fashion capitals of the world, and the shops are open year round.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading -->\n<h2>MILAN TRANSPORTATION</h2>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>A great aspect about visiting Milan is there is a regular bus line running to and from the airport and city center. These lines are the&nbsp;<strong>73 and 73X buses</strong>, each with a very similar route and high efficiency. The 73X is a little faster, and both stop at the city center for about a 20-minute ride.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>There are no trains or trams to and from the airport. The public transport in Milan is generally great, with plenty of trams, buses, and subway stations in the city. This makes traveling easy, especially if you want to see the city’s tourist attractions with one day in Milan.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading -->\n<h2>WHAT TO DO IN ONE DAY IN MILAN</h2>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>If you have one day in Milan, you have your pick of things to do in Milan to fill your time.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":3} -->\n<h3>DUOMO</h3>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Arguably Milan’s most famous landmark, the Duomo is a cathedral of epic proportions. While at first glance it might not appear like the Duomo is large, once you’re on the inside it becomes crystal clear why it’s considered one of the largest cathedrals in the world.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>A little background on the Milan Duomo – it is the 5th largest cathedral in the world. They started building it in 1386, and it took over 600 years to finish building. There were many revisions as new rulers took over each century, delaying the completion.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Finally, in 1805, Napoleon Bonaparte ordered it to be finished, and the construction was complete. A statue of him was put on one of the spires as a form of thank you, and Napoleon was crowned the king of Italy in the Duomo.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>The best part about visiting the Duomo is that there is no entrance fee, even though there are lines. However, there is a fee to enter the Crypt and the roof, with tickets priced at&nbsp;<strong>3 and 9 euros</strong>&nbsp;respectively. Admission hours are from&nbsp;<strong>8 am to 7 pm</strong>, so it’s a great place to check out if you only have one day in Milan to spend.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:image {\"id\":7960,\"align\":\"center\"} -->\n<div class=\"wp-block-image\"><figure class=\"aligncenter\"><img src=\"https://postcardstoseattle.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/08/one-day-in-milan-duomo.jpg\" alt=\"one day in milan duomo\" class=\"wp-image-7960\"/></figure></div>\n<!-- /wp:image -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":3} -->\n<h3>THE LAST SUPPER</h3>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>What’s rightly called one of the world’s most famous paintings, this is a piece of history to see if you can only spend one day in Milan. It’s still located in the same place to this very day, in the church of Mother Mary of Grace.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Due to the technique used to create this masterpiece, it’s slowly decaying. Sometime in the future, it’ll completely rot, leaving only the reproductions behind. Entry fee is&nbsp;<strong>10 euros</strong>, and there’s a schedule for entering as the room is not allowed to be crowded. However, it’s well worth the visit of such a wonderful masterpiece, and should be included in any Milan itinerary.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":3} -->\n<h3>DINNER AT A LOCAL RESTAURANT</h3>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Italian food is probably the world’s most famous type of cuisine, but when you’re in Milan forget all about pasta and pizza. There are many other specialties, especially in Milano. Each region of Italy has its own regional cooking, and one of the delicacies in Milano is the risotto.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Having dinner in a local restaurant, while not always a cheap affair, is always a delicious one. When you spend one day in Milan, it’s still time that’s well spent.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":3} -->\n<h3>CASTELO SFORZESCO</h3>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>This is a castle that makes you feel small like a mouse. An expansively large castle, it has beautiful stonework and sweeping courtyards filled with fountains and statues. There’s also an imposing wall dotted with guard towers. Originally constructed in the 14<sup>th</sup>&nbsp;century, it was later renovated in the 15<sup>th</sup>century.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Castle Sforzesco is located in the heart of Milan, and the entrance fee is&nbsp;<strong>5 euros.</strong>&nbsp;While there are plenty of museums in and around the castle that have different entry fees, &nbsp;the castle is more than worth a visit on its own. This should be considered as part of any Milan itinerary.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:image {\"id\":7964,\"align\":\"center\"} -->\n<div class=\"wp-block-image\"><figure class=\"aligncenter\"><img src=\"https://postcardstoseattle.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/08/one-day-in-milan-sforzesco-castle.jpg\" alt=\"milan itinerary sforzesco castle\" class=\"wp-image-7964\"/></figure></div>\n<!-- /wp:image -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":3} -->\n<h3>PINACOTECA DI BRERA</h3>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>If you’re even remotely interested in Italian art, then the Pinacoteca di Brera is definitely the place for you during your one day in Milan. It’s a &nbsp;fine art gallery that houses numerous artists and has a unique history. Before being converted into a museum, it was used as a Christian convent and a national library.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Tons of amazing works from renowned artists can be found inside this gallery, including Raphael, Bellini, Rubens, Correggio, and many more. It’s easily accessible as it’s quite near the heart of Milan, and regular admission hours are from&nbsp;<strong>8:30 am to 7:15 pm</strong>.&nbsp;Note that there is an exception of Thursday when it closes at 10:15 pm. Regular tickets are&nbsp;<strong>10 euros</strong>&nbsp;with some exceptions, such as admission being free on the first Sunday of every month.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":3} -->\n<h3>SHOPPING</h3>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>As one of the world’s fashion capitals, spending one day in Milan shopping for clothing is one of the favorite pastimes for both tourists and Milanese alike. The most famous district for shopping in Milan is the&nbsp;<strong>Tony Quadrilatero Della Moda</strong>&nbsp;with its streets lined with many boutiques and shops.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>However, there are many other options for different budgets as well. Clothing, perfume, jewelry, and trinkets of all sorts are sizes are readily available, and constantly sought after.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:image {\"id\":7956,\"align\":\"center\"} -->\n<div class=\"wp-block-image\"><figure class=\"aligncenter\"><img src=\"https://postcardstoseattle.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/08/one-day-in-milan-shopping.jpg\" alt=\"shopping in milan itinerary\" class=\"wp-image-7956\"/></figure></div>\n<!-- /wp:image -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":3} -->\n<h3>SANT AMBROGIO</h3>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>This church is a fantastic example of Milanese history, as it’s an incredibly old structure. It was originally consecrated in the late 4<sup>th</sup>&nbsp;century, and was later reconstructed in a Lombard Romanesque style in the 11<sup>th</sup>&nbsp;century. This church is considered one of the pillars on which Milan was built upon.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>As the city grew around the church, it became more and more apparent just how important the Sant Ambrogio church is, both culturally and historically. There is no entrance fee, only a modest fee of&nbsp;<strong>2 euros</strong>&nbsp;for the museum. The church is open from&nbsp;<strong>10 am till noon</strong>, and then from&nbsp;<strong>2:30 pm to 6 pm</strong>.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":3} -->\n<h3>LEONARDO DA VINCI NATIONAL MUSEUM OF SCIENCE AND TECHNOLOGY</h3>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>It’s safe to say that Leonardo Da Vinci was one of the biggest geniuses in the history of mankind. He was an artist, an engineer, a scientist, an inventor, and so much more, and his genius won’t ever be forgotten. This a museum dedicated to his inventions, arts, and crafts, and is considered one of the most important museums in the world. You’ll definitely want to see this during your one day in Milan.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>It’s an amazing place to visit, and absolutely inspiring, as it feels like the spirit of Leonardo Da Vinci is still present in his inventions. There is a moderate entrance fee of&nbsp;<strong>10 euros</strong>. Admission hours are from&nbsp;<strong>10 am to 6 pm</strong>, and this museum should part of everyone’s Milan itinerary.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":3} -->\n<h3>MILAN ARCHAEOLOGY MUSEUM</h3>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>The entirety of Italy is drenched in history, and Milan is no exception. The city’s been a large and important hub since the ancient days, back when it was called Mediolanum. This museum is a building that houses physical proof of Milan’s importance.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>It’s not only about the importance, though, as Milanese history is downright fascinating. Many of the exhibits focus on the evolution of Milan as a whole, right from the Etruscan influences thousands of years ago to the Middle Ages. The museum is open from 9 am to 5:30 pm, with a price of&nbsp;<strong>5 euros</strong>&nbsp;per ticket.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":3} -->\n<h3>TEATRO ALLA SCALA</h3>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Few other opera houses in the world can boast about the amount of activity they’ve had like La Scala Opera. It’s a historic building that’s housed numerous shows throughout the centuries. Every play and opera that it’s housed has been a fantastic treat for its audiences.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>While the entrance is free, the real stars of the show are the operas. These can get pricey depending on which one is currently playing. There is a museum that’s open from&nbsp;<strong>9 am to 5:30 pm</strong>&nbsp;with an admission fee of&nbsp;<strong>9 euros</strong>.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":3} -->\n<h3>PIAZZA MERCANTI</h3>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>An old and important square near the heart of the city, the Piazza Mercanti used to be the central and largest hub in medieval Milan. Its name means the square of the merchants, as this is where the trade of the highest order used to be done. You’ll want to stop here during your one day in Milan to take pictures.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>The square is lined with numerous statues, old buildings, palaces, and all around irresistible charm. It’s considered one of the most important historic squares of Milan and is definitely a place that everyone should put in their Milan itinerary.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:image {\"id\":7963,\"align\":\"center\"} -->\n<div class=\"wp-block-image\"><figure class=\"aligncenter\"><img src=\"https://postcardstoseattle.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/08/one-day-in-milan-piazza-mercanti.jpg\" alt=\"what to do in milan piazza mercanti\" class=\"wp-image-7963\"/></figure></div>\n<!-- /wp:image -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":3} -->\n<h3>PARCO SEMPIONE</h3>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Milan is a busy city, no doubt. It can get very crowded at times because of its popularity, and one of the best places to relax and unwind is the Parco Sempione.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Located right behind Castelo Sforzesco, its open and peaceful grounds are amazing for anyone looking for a relaxing walk. It’s also great for casual biking. Parco Sempione all beautifully landscaped and easily accessible, and definitely one of the best places to see when you only have time for one day in Milan.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading -->\n<h2>WHERE TO EAT IN MILAN</h2>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>There are many restaurants in Milan to choose from, but here are a few places I recommend when you have one day in Milan.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":3} -->\n<h3>PESCARIA</h3>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>A very unique little restaurant that feels as if it’s transported directly from a little seaside town, this eatery is a popular choice among locals and visitors alike, and serves seafood with a unique Italian twist.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":3} -->\n<h3>UN POSTO A MILANO</h3>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>The greatest part about this restaurant is the seasonal menu. The dishes are different depending on the season, and besides quality, freshness is the most important focus.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":3} -->\n<h3>DONGIO</h3>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>An old-fashioned restaurant with old school values, this is an eatery of which the likes are getting increasingly rare. Its focus is serving simple Italian food at decent prices and is constantly visited by locals, which is always a good sign.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":3} -->\n<h3>LANGOSTERIA</h3>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Arguably the city’s best seafood restaurant, the Langosteria is an upscale location but without the unnecessary posturing. Amazing food and a great ambiance is the focus, with a warmth not typical to restaurants of the type.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":3} -->\n<h3>PIZZERIA GINO SORBILLO</h3>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>If you’re looking for excellent pizza that’s close to the city center, then this is the perfect place when you only have one day in Milan. It has a family business feel, but one that operates really efficiently, and that shows in the quality of the food.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:image {\"id\":757,\"align\":\"center\",\"linkDestination\":\"custom\"} -->\n<div class=\"wp-block-image\"><figure class=\"aligncenter\"><a href=\"http://postcardstoseattle.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/08/IMG_5949.jpg\"><img src=\"https://postcardstoseattle.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/08/IMG_5949.jpg\" alt=\"where to eat in milan\" class=\"wp-image-757\"/></a></figure></div>\n<!-- /wp:image -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading -->\n<h2>WHERE TO STAY IN MILAN</h2>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>There are many places to stay in Milan, so here are a few hotels I recommend.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":3} -->\n<h3>HOTEL MILANO NAVIGLI</h3>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>A very affordable hotel with decently sized rooms and a lively atmosphere, it’s located near the Navigli district. This is a very active area in the city and one where you can see canals (even though they’re artificial). <strong>Read reviews on TripAdvisor | Check prices on Hotels.com</strong></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":3} -->\n<h3>BIOCITY HOTEL</h3>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>When it comes to the Biocity then green is the name of the game, as eco-friendliness is one of its primary focuses. The rooms are great and decently sized, and the service is equally amazing. <strong>Read reviews on TripAdvisor</strong></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":3} -->\n<h3>EUROHOTEL</h3>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>This Milan hotel is not only near the Duomo but it’s also very affordable. This is an extremely rare thing, especially since it’s a hotel of great quality.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->', 'HOW TO SPEND ONE DAY IN MILAN, ITALY', '', 'publish', 'open', 'open', '', 'how-to-spend-one-day-in-milan-italy', '', '', '2019-04-21 04:12:29', '2019-04-21 04:12:29', '', 0, 'http://localhost/wordpress/?p=257', 0, 'post', '', 0),
(258, 1, '2019-04-21 04:11:32', '2019-04-21 04:11:32', '', 'one-day-in-milan-city-center', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'closed', '', 'one-day-in-milan-city-center', '', '', '2019-04-21 04:11:32', '2019-04-21 04:11:32', '', 257, 'http://localhost/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/2019/04/one-day-in-milan-city-center.jpg', 0, 'attachment', 'image/jpeg', 0),
(259, 1, '2019-04-21 04:12:29', '2019-04-21 04:12:29', '<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>One of the most beautiful cities in all of Europe, Milan has been visited by tourists for centuries. Practically swimming with art, culture, and history, spending one day in Milan is a time well-spent. When you’re planning what to do in Milan, don’t forget about the amazing landmarks of the city, many of which are easy to spot as you walk around.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Table of Contents</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:list -->\n<ul><li>Best Time to Visit Milan</li><li>Milan Transportation</li><li>What to Do in One Day in Milan</li><li>Where to Eat in Milan</li><li>Where to Stay in Milan</li><li>Day Trips from Milan</li></ul>\n<!-- /wp:list -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading -->\n<h2>BEST TIME TO VISIT MILAN</h2>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Generally, there is no best time to visit Milan, as it’s great to visit any time of the year. If you’re looking to have a more peaceful time and to avoid many of the tourists, then&nbsp;<strong>April to May</strong>&nbsp;are ideal months. The same is true for&nbsp;<strong>September and October</strong>&nbsp;as well.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>On the other hand, if you want to have the full tourist experience, then the summer months are ideal for that. The climate in Milan is quite warm, and the weather is normally great. Due to this, it’s no wonder that summer in Milan is the height of the tourist season. There is no specific season for fashion shopping, though, since it’s one of the fashion capitals of the world, and the shops are open year round.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading -->\n<h2>MILAN TRANSPORTATION</h2>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>A great aspect about visiting Milan is there is a regular bus line running to and from the airport and city center. These lines are the&nbsp;<strong>73 and 73X buses</strong>, each with a very similar route and high efficiency. The 73X is a little faster, and both stop at the city center for about a 20-minute ride.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>There are no trains or trams to and from the airport. The public transport in Milan is generally great, with plenty of trams, buses, and subway stations in the city. This makes traveling easy, especially if you want to see the city’s tourist attractions with one day in Milan.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading -->\n<h2>WHAT TO DO IN ONE DAY IN MILAN</h2>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>If you have one day in Milan, you have your pick of things to do in Milan to fill your time.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":3} -->\n<h3>DUOMO</h3>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Arguably Milan’s most famous landmark, the Duomo is a cathedral of epic proportions. While at first glance it might not appear like the Duomo is large, once you’re on the inside it becomes crystal clear why it’s considered one of the largest cathedrals in the world.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>A little background on the Milan Duomo – it is the 5th largest cathedral in the world. They started building it in 1386, and it took over 600 years to finish building. There were many revisions as new rulers took over each century, delaying the completion.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Finally, in 1805, Napoleon Bonaparte ordered it to be finished, and the construction was complete. A statue of him was put on one of the spires as a form of thank you, and Napoleon was crowned the king of Italy in the Duomo.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>The best part about visiting the Duomo is that there is no entrance fee, even though there are lines. However, there is a fee to enter the Crypt and the roof, with tickets priced at&nbsp;<strong>3 and 9 euros</strong>&nbsp;respectively. Admission hours are from&nbsp;<strong>8 am to 7 pm</strong>, so it’s a great place to check out if you only have one day in Milan to spend.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:image {\"id\":7960,\"align\":\"center\"} -->\n<div class=\"wp-block-image\"><figure class=\"aligncenter\"><img src=\"https://postcardstoseattle.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/08/one-day-in-milan-duomo.jpg\" alt=\"one day in milan duomo\" class=\"wp-image-7960\"/></figure></div>\n<!-- /wp:image -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":3} -->\n<h3>THE LAST SUPPER</h3>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>What’s rightly called one of the world’s most famous paintings, this is a piece of history to see if you can only spend one day in Milan. It’s still located in the same place to this very day, in the church of Mother Mary of Grace.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Due to the technique used to create this masterpiece, it’s slowly decaying. Sometime in the future, it’ll completely rot, leaving only the reproductions behind. Entry fee is&nbsp;<strong>10 euros</strong>, and there’s a schedule for entering as the room is not allowed to be crowded. However, it’s well worth the visit of such a wonderful masterpiece, and should be included in any Milan itinerary.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":3} -->\n<h3>DINNER AT A LOCAL RESTAURANT</h3>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Italian food is probably the world’s most famous type of cuisine, but when you’re in Milan forget all about pasta and pizza. There are many other specialties, especially in Milano. Each region of Italy has its own regional cooking, and one of the delicacies in Milano is the risotto.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Having dinner in a local restaurant, while not always a cheap affair, is always a delicious one. When you spend one day in Milan, it’s still time that’s well spent.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":3} -->\n<h3>CASTELO SFORZESCO</h3>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>This is a castle that makes you feel small like a mouse. An expansively large castle, it has beautiful stonework and sweeping courtyards filled with fountains and statues. There’s also an imposing wall dotted with guard towers. Originally constructed in the 14<sup>th</sup>&nbsp;century, it was later renovated in the 15<sup>th</sup>century.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Castle Sforzesco is located in the heart of Milan, and the entrance fee is&nbsp;<strong>5 euros.</strong>&nbsp;While there are plenty of museums in and around the castle that have different entry fees, &nbsp;the castle is more than worth a visit on its own. This should be considered as part of any Milan itinerary.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:image {\"id\":7964,\"align\":\"center\"} -->\n<div class=\"wp-block-image\"><figure class=\"aligncenter\"><img src=\"https://postcardstoseattle.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/08/one-day-in-milan-sforzesco-castle.jpg\" alt=\"milan itinerary sforzesco castle\" class=\"wp-image-7964\"/></figure></div>\n<!-- /wp:image -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":3} -->\n<h3>PINACOTECA DI BRERA</h3>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>If you’re even remotely interested in Italian art, then the Pinacoteca di Brera is definitely the place for you during your one day in Milan. It’s a &nbsp;fine art gallery that houses numerous artists and has a unique history. Before being converted into a museum, it was used as a Christian convent and a national library.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Tons of amazing works from renowned artists can be found inside this gallery, including Raphael, Bellini, Rubens, Correggio, and many more. It’s easily accessible as it’s quite near the heart of Milan, and regular admission hours are from&nbsp;<strong>8:30 am to 7:15 pm</strong>.&nbsp;Note that there is an exception of Thursday when it closes at 10:15 pm. Regular tickets are&nbsp;<strong>10 euros</strong>&nbsp;with some exceptions, such as admission being free on the first Sunday of every month.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":3} -->\n<h3>SHOPPING</h3>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>As one of the world’s fashion capitals, spending one day in Milan shopping for clothing is one of the favorite pastimes for both tourists and Milanese alike. The most famous district for shopping in Milan is the&nbsp;<strong>Tony Quadrilatero Della Moda</strong>&nbsp;with its streets lined with many boutiques and shops.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>However, there are many other options for different budgets as well. Clothing, perfume, jewelry, and trinkets of all sorts are sizes are readily available, and constantly sought after.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:image {\"id\":7956,\"align\":\"center\"} -->\n<div class=\"wp-block-image\"><figure class=\"aligncenter\"><img src=\"https://postcardstoseattle.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/08/one-day-in-milan-shopping.jpg\" alt=\"shopping in milan itinerary\" class=\"wp-image-7956\"/></figure></div>\n<!-- /wp:image -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":3} -->\n<h3>SANT AMBROGIO</h3>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>This church is a fantastic example of Milanese history, as it’s an incredibly old structure. It was originally consecrated in the late 4<sup>th</sup>&nbsp;century, and was later reconstructed in a Lombard Romanesque style in the 11<sup>th</sup>&nbsp;century. This church is considered one of the pillars on which Milan was built upon.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>As the city grew around the church, it became more and more apparent just how important the Sant Ambrogio church is, both culturally and historically. There is no entrance fee, only a modest fee of&nbsp;<strong>2 euros</strong>&nbsp;for the museum. The church is open from&nbsp;<strong>10 am till noon</strong>, and then from&nbsp;<strong>2:30 pm to 6 pm</strong>.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":3} -->\n<h3>LEONARDO DA VINCI NATIONAL MUSEUM OF SCIENCE AND TECHNOLOGY</h3>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>It’s safe to say that Leonardo Da Vinci was one of the biggest geniuses in the history of mankind. He was an artist, an engineer, a scientist, an inventor, and so much more, and his genius won’t ever be forgotten. This a museum dedicated to his inventions, arts, and crafts, and is considered one of the most important museums in the world. You’ll definitely want to see this during your one day in Milan.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>It’s an amazing place to visit, and absolutely inspiring, as it feels like the spirit of Leonardo Da Vinci is still present in his inventions. There is a moderate entrance fee of&nbsp;<strong>10 euros</strong>. Admission hours are from&nbsp;<strong>10 am to 6 pm</strong>, and this museum should part of everyone’s Milan itinerary.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":3} -->\n<h3>MILAN ARCHAEOLOGY MUSEUM</h3>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>The entirety of Italy is drenched in history, and Milan is no exception. The city’s been a large and important hub since the ancient days, back when it was called Mediolanum. This museum is a building that houses physical proof of Milan’s importance.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>It’s not only about the importance, though, as Milanese history is downright fascinating. Many of the exhibits focus on the evolution of Milan as a whole, right from the Etruscan influences thousands of years ago to the Middle Ages. The museum is open from 9 am to 5:30 pm, with a price of&nbsp;<strong>5 euros</strong>&nbsp;per ticket.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":3} -->\n<h3>TEATRO ALLA SCALA</h3>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Few other opera houses in the world can boast about the amount of activity they’ve had like La Scala Opera. It’s a historic building that’s housed numerous shows throughout the centuries. Every play and opera that it’s housed has been a fantastic treat for its audiences.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>While the entrance is free, the real stars of the show are the operas. These can get pricey depending on which one is currently playing. There is a museum that’s open from&nbsp;<strong>9 am to 5:30 pm</strong>&nbsp;with an admission fee of&nbsp;<strong>9 euros</strong>.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":3} -->\n<h3>PIAZZA MERCANTI</h3>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>An old and important square near the heart of the city, the Piazza Mercanti used to be the central and largest hub in medieval Milan. Its name means the square of the merchants, as this is where the trade of the highest order used to be done. You’ll want to stop here during your one day in Milan to take pictures.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>The square is lined with numerous statues, old buildings, palaces, and all around irresistible charm. It’s considered one of the most important historic squares of Milan and is definitely a place that everyone should put in their Milan itinerary.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:image {\"id\":7963,\"align\":\"center\"} -->\n<div class=\"wp-block-image\"><figure class=\"aligncenter\"><img src=\"https://postcardstoseattle.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/08/one-day-in-milan-piazza-mercanti.jpg\" alt=\"what to do in milan piazza mercanti\" class=\"wp-image-7963\"/></figure></div>\n<!-- /wp:image -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":3} -->\n<h3>PARCO SEMPIONE</h3>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Milan is a busy city, no doubt. It can get very crowded at times because of its popularity, and one of the best places to relax and unwind is the Parco Sempione.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Located right behind Castelo Sforzesco, its open and peaceful grounds are amazing for anyone looking for a relaxing walk. It’s also great for casual biking. Parco Sempione all beautifully landscaped and easily accessible, and definitely one of the best places to see when you only have time for one day in Milan.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading -->\n<h2>WHERE TO EAT IN MILAN</h2>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>There are many restaurants in Milan to choose from, but here are a few places I recommend when you have one day in Milan.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":3} -->\n<h3>PESCARIA</h3>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>A very unique little restaurant that feels as if it’s transported directly from a little seaside town, this eatery is a popular choice among locals and visitors alike, and serves seafood with a unique Italian twist.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":3} -->\n<h3>UN POSTO A MILANO</h3>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>The greatest part about this restaurant is the seasonal menu. The dishes are different depending on the season, and besides quality, freshness is the most important focus.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":3} -->\n<h3>DONGIO</h3>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>An old-fashioned restaurant with old school values, this is an eatery of which the likes are getting increasingly rare. Its focus is serving simple Italian food at decent prices and is constantly visited by locals, which is always a good sign.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":3} -->\n<h3>LANGOSTERIA</h3>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Arguably the city’s best seafood restaurant, the Langosteria is an upscale location but without the unnecessary posturing. Amazing food and a great ambiance is the focus, with a warmth not typical to restaurants of the type.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":3} -->\n<h3>PIZZERIA GINO SORBILLO</h3>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>If you’re looking for excellent pizza that’s close to the city center, then this is the perfect place when you only have one day in Milan. It has a family business feel, but one that operates really efficiently, and that shows in the quality of the food.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:image {\"id\":757,\"align\":\"center\",\"linkDestination\":\"custom\"} -->\n<div class=\"wp-block-image\"><figure class=\"aligncenter\"><a href=\"http://postcardstoseattle.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/08/IMG_5949.jpg\"><img src=\"https://postcardstoseattle.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/08/IMG_5949.jpg\" alt=\"where to eat in milan\" class=\"wp-image-757\"/></a></figure></div>\n<!-- /wp:image -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading -->\n<h2>WHERE TO STAY IN MILAN</h2>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>There are many places to stay in Milan, so here are a few hotels I recommend.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":3} -->\n<h3>HOTEL MILANO NAVIGLI</h3>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>A very affordable hotel with decently sized rooms and a lively atmosphere, it’s located near the Navigli district. This is a very active area in the city and one where you can see canals (even though they’re artificial). <strong>Read reviews on TripAdvisor | Check prices on Hotels.com</strong></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":3} -->\n<h3>BIOCITY HOTEL</h3>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>When it comes to the Biocity then green is the name of the game, as eco-friendliness is one of its primary focuses. The rooms are great and decently sized, and the service is equally amazing. <strong>Read reviews on TripAdvisor</strong></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":3} -->\n<h3>EUROHOTEL</h3>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>This Milan hotel is not only near the Duomo but it’s also very affordable. This is an extremely rare thing, especially since it’s a hotel of great quality.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->', 'HOW TO SPEND ONE DAY IN MILAN, ITALY', '', 'inherit', 'closed', 'closed', '', '257-revision-v1', '', '', '2019-04-21 04:12:29', '2019-04-21 04:12:29', '', 257, 'http://localhost/wordpress/2019/04/21/257-revision-v1/', 0, 'revision', '', 0);
